r 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19311022.2.149\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|| Auckland Colts|| 13 || Eastern Suburbs (Sydney) || 18 || Carlaw Park # 1, 4pm\n|-\n|}\n\n== Representative season ==\nIt was a very quiet year on the representative team front. There was a match played between North Island and South Island, but the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team's only match was for the Northern Union Cup against [[Northland rugby league team|Northland]]. In a surprise result Northland had defeated [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] to lift the trophy. [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] challenged for it but could only manage a 19 all draw and so Northland retained it. Auckland junior teams played two matches and a colts side played against the touring [[Sydney Roosters|Eastern Suburbs]] team from [[Sydney]] who were the premiers of the [[New South Wales Rugby League]].\n\n=== Representative fixtures ===\nOnly a small number of fixtures were played in the 1931 season partly owing to the fact that [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] did not hold the Northern Union Cup. Also the touring [[Sydney Roosters|Eastern Suburbs]] team from Sydney had matches with club sides organised for them.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1931 Auckland Representative Fixtures\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Representative Fixture\n| 15 Aug<ref>{{cite news\n| title =High Scoring Game/North Island League Team/Too Superior for South/Margin of Twenty-Nine Points\n| page = 11\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20953\n| date = 17 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310817.2.130\n| accessdate = 26 October 2019}}</ref>\n|| North Island || 52 || South Island || 23 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Northern Union Cup\n| 26 Sep<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Fixture/Auckland and Northland/Match Ends in a Draw\n| page = 10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20989\n| date = 28 September 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310928.2.131.5\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 19 || Northland || 19 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3:15pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Representative Match\n| 17 Oct<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Wednesday Reps V Junior Reps\n| page =9\n| work =New Zealand Herald| volume= LXVIII| issue= 21007\n| date = 19 October 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19311019.2.136\n| accessdate = 28 September 2019}}</ref>\n|| Wednesday Representatives|| 23 || Auckland Junior Representatives || 6 || Carlaw Park\n|-\n|}\n\n== Annual general meetings and club news ==\n*[[Auckland Rugby League]] held their annual general meeting in the Chamber of Commerce, Swanson Street on Thursday 16 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=82\n| date = 8 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310408.2.172.3\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> At a later meeting they voted to adopt the motion whereby its grading of referees and appointments of them for matches would be done by a group of three, consisting of two of its members and a representative of the [[Auckland Rugby League]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Appointment of Referees/Management Representation Approved\n| page = 12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=98\n| date = 28 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310428.2.125\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> Tenders were requested for the lease of the Carlaw Park Refreshment Stall, and for the rights of the Rugby League Gazette.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland Rugby Football League\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=87\n| date = 14 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310414.2.188.3\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Auckland Rugby League]] Junior Management Committee held their annual meeting at the Grey Buildings on Tuesday, 31 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20834\n| date = 28 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310328.2.10.4\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> After the reports were given by club delegates the prospect was for a record season in terms of team and player numbers. Mr. C. Adamson was elected Chairman, with his deputy Mr. W. Lusty.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Lower Grade Prospects\n| page = 15\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20837\n| date = 1 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310401.2.151\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> During the season the Junior Management Committee became dissatisfied with their chairman Mr. C. Adamson because he voted contrarily to their position at an Auckland Rugby League meeting. They subsequently voted him out of the position. Mr. George Rhodes, chairman of the senior management committee attended a later meeting to say that Adamson was on the senior board as an independent representative, not as a representative of the Junior Management Committee and their dismissal of him was unjustified. A vote was then held over who should be chairman with Mr. J. H. Eddowes nominated along with Mr. Adamson and the former won by 10 votes to 6.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Junior Board Trouble/Mediation by Mr. Rhodes/New Chairman Nominated\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 183\n| date = 5 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310805.2.122\n| accessdate = 26 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*Auckland Rugby League Primary School Management Committee\n*[[Auckland Rugby League]] Referees Association annual meeting was held at the League Rooms, Grey Buildings on 30 March. The report stated that membership had increased and the standard of refereeing was maintained at a high level.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Referees Association\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 77\n| date = 2 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310402.2.161\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Akarana Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual general meeting at Carlaw Park on Thursday 9 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20842\n| date = 8 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310408.2.165.5\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Avondale League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Hick's Tearooms, Avondale on Wednesday 25 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 69\n| date = 23 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310323.2.194.2\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> There was an attendance of about twenty players and the cash credit was \u00a37 10/8. The club voted to thank Mr. H. P. Burton for the use of his ground where the majority of their matches were played in 1930.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Avondale Club\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 73\n| date = 27 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310327.2.138.9\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[City Rovers]] annual meeting was held at Carlaw Park on Sunday 22 March to discuss the annual report, balance sheet, general business and to elect officers. Seventy five people attended the meeting where the annual report showed a balance of \u00a333 10/6. They stated that their chances of winning the title the year before was spoiled by the fact that they lost four players to the New Zealand team which toured Australia. They were aiming to have teams in all of the junior grades.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Annual Meetings Held/The City Club\u2019s Season\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20832\n| date = 26 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310326.2.34.7\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Devonport United Football Club]] annual general meeting was held in the Labour Rooms (above Hellaby's), Devonport on Monday 30 March regarding the election of officers and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20830\n| date = 24 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310324.2.158.8\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> About fifty members attended and the balance sheet showed a credit of \u00a39 7/2.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Question of Status/Suggestion by Official\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 76\n| date = 31 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310331.2.139\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie United League Football Club]] held their annual general meeting at the Club's Training Shed, Ellerslie on Monday 23 March. They requested that everybody attend as it would be their final meeting due to the league enforced merger with Otahuhu.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 68\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310321.2.177.1\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*Ellerslie-Otahuhu United League Football Club held their first general meeting at the Ellerslie club's training shed opposite the railway station on Monday 30 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page =20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 74\n| date = 28 March 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310328.2.188.5\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They had practice for all grades on Saturday 18 April to make final arrangements for all teams as there was a merger of Ellerslie, Otahuhu and Mangere.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 90\n| date = 17 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310417.2.156.1\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Glen Lynn League Football Club]] held their annual general meeting at the Delta Theatre on Monday 23 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=67\n| date = 20 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310320.2.129.4\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> The Glen Lynn club wrote a letter to the New Lynn Borough Council asking for assistance in acquiring a playing area. The council intended to give the club details of an existing league football area on Great North Road in New Lynn which had been used by the New Lynn club prior to the joining of New Lynn and Glen Eden.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local Bodies/New Lynn Borough Council\n| page = 5\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 70\n| date = 24 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310324.2.48\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Kingsland Athletic Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Liberty Luncheon Rooms at the top of Symonds Street on Monday 30 March to discuss the annual report and balance sheet.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 68\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310321.2.177.1\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They held a further Special General Meeting on Thursday 16 April at Donovan's Gym, Parnell with all juniors requested to roll up.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 87\n| date = 14 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310414.2.188.8\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> The Kingsland club amalgamated with the Marist club after they lost Senior A grade status.\n\n*[[Marist Saints|Marist Brothers Old Boys League Football Club]] annual meeting held at Donovan's Gymnasium, Parnell on Monday 30 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20834\n| date = 28 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310328.2.10.4\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mangere Rugby League Football Club]] held a meeting in the Strand Theatre Hall, Onehunga on Wednesday, 29 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20859\n| date = 29 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310429.2.160.8\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mt Albert Lions|Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the King George Hall in [[Mount Albert, New Zealand|Mount Albert]] on Thursday, 5 March to discuss the annual report, balance sheet, election of officers, and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20812\n| date = 3 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310303.2.159.7\n| accessdate = 2 October 2019}}</ref> There first practice was held at the club's grounds on Springleigh Avenue on Saturday, 11 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 83\n| date = 9 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310409.2.218.4\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> At a Management Committee meeting on 22 April Mount Albert applied to have its Senior B team (who had played in the Senior B Grade \u2013 effectively the 2nd division of senior teams in 1930) regraded to first junior.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Management Meeting\n| page = 17\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 95\n| date = 23 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310423.2.157\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mt Wellington Rugby League Football Club]] annual meeting was held at the Abattoir, Westfield on Tuesday 24 March to discuss the annual report and balance sheet, the election of officers, and general business. Players and intending players were requested to attend.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20826\n| date = 19 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310319.2.173.3\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Newmarket Rugby League Football Club]] annual meeting was held at the Club Room 235, Khyber Pass, Thursday 26 March. All players and intending players were invited to attend.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=44\n| date = 21 February 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310221.2.162.3\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Newton Rangers]] Football Club annual meeting was held at the Y.M.C.A on Wellesley St. East on Monday 23 March. All vice presidents, members and intending members were invited to attend including late Senior B players (players from Senior B clubs who no longer had senior teams).<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue=20822\n| date = 14 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310314.2.8.2\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> There was a large attendance with Mr. W. Badley presiding over the meeting and Mr. W. Monteith was elected patron<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Newton Club\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20832\n| date = 26 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310326.2.34.7\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>..\n\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers Football Club]] annual general meeting was held at the Foresters' Hall, Birkenhead on Thursday 12 March to discuss \"business important\".<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20818\n| date = 10 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310310.2.172.4\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> They donated \u00a32 2s to the Mayors fund for Napier Earthquake fund.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Mayor\u2019s Fund/Further Contributions/Total of \u00a322,969 to Date\n| page = 11\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20818\n| date = 10 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310310.2.120\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> The annual meeting of the [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers Football Club]] was their 21st. The president of the club was Mr. A. E. Greenslade who was also the mayor of Northcote. The club report stated that they had a membership of 115 and fielded six teams in the league competition, and that this made them the fourth largest club in [[Auckland]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers\n| page =13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 61\n| date = 13 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310313.2.157.5\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu Rugby League Football Club]] were given use of the Sturges Park and Princes Street playing grounds in a shared arrangement with rugby by the Otahuhu Borough Council.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Otahuhu Borough Council\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 84\n| date = 10 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310410.2.24\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Papakura Sea Eagles|Papakura Rugby League Football Club]] The Papakura Rugby Club had decided to disband and play league instead.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Manukau Union\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20829\n| date = 23 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310323.2.163.9\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They held their first ever meeting in the Parish Hall, Papakura on Thursday, 26 March. Officials of the [[Auckland Rugby League]] were present. All members, intending members, players and supporters were invited to attend.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20828\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310321.2.10.1\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> Following the meeting a club was formed with 60 players enrolling.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papakura Club Formed\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20828\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310321.2.141.4\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Papatoetoe Rugby League Club]] held their annual meeting in mid April. There was a large attendance and it was decided to nominate five teams for the season, namely third grade open, fourth grade, fifth grade, sixth grade, and a schoolboys.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papatoetoe Club\u2019s Meeting\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 90\n| date = 17 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310417.2.136\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> The club held its annual ball in the Papatoetoe Town Hall on 24 July. The venue was decorated in the club's colours of blue and gold.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papatoetoe Dance\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 174\n| date = 25 July 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310725.2.134.3\n| accessdate = 24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Sailing Club's Hall on Thursday 19 March to discuss business, balance-sheet, and election of officers.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 65\n| date = 18 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310318.2.190.3\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Leys Institute, Ponsonby on Monday 30 March to receive their annual report and balance sheet, elect officers, and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 22\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20831\n| date = 25 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310325.2.180.5\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> 80 members attended the meeting and the report referred to how successful the club had been, especially with the senior side winning the Monteith Shield, Roope Rooster, and Thistle Cup. The third grade open team was particularly good and the schoolboy team consisted of players from Ponsonby, Curran Street, and Bayfield Schools.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Referees Association/Ponsonby Club\u2019s Meeting\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 77\n| date = 2 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310402.2.161\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers Football Club]] annual meeting was held in the Gaiety Hall, Surrey Crescent on Friday 20 March to discuss the annual report and statement of accounts, and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 59\n| date = 11 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310311.2.187.7\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> About 100 members were in attendance. The report showed that the club had fielded 12 teams in 1930 with four winning the championship. Trophies were presented as follows \u2013 Lauder Cup, fourth grade; Milicich Cup, seventh grade A team; Walker Shield: second grade; and a trophy to the schoolboys who tied for first place.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Richmond Club\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20832\n| date = 26 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310326.2.34.7\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They held an additional meeting for all prospective Senior, Senior B, and Second Grade players at Grey Lynn Park on Wednesday, 8 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 24\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 77\n| date = 2 April 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310402.2.171.6\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> On 16 May the Richmond club performed the notable feat of having all eight of its A teams winning their matches, although its Seventh Grade B team was defeated, and the 5th Grade team's victory was by default.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Manukau and Richmond\n| page = 12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 115\n| date = 18 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310518.2.142.11\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season the Third Grade captain for [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]], Mr. George Williams drowned in a fishing accident in Breaker Bay, Wellington.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Three Drowned/Wellington Tragedy/Small Fishing Boat Lost/Story Told by Survivor/Wrecked on Submerged Rock\n| page = 7\n| work = [[Auckland Star]] | volume=LXII| issue=97\n| date = 27 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310427.2.83\n| accessdate = 23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Junior Management Affairs\n| page = 10\n| work = [[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 201\n| date = 26 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310826.2.125\n| accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:1931 in New Zealand rugby league|Auckland Rugby League]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\nThe 1931 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was its 23rd.\n\nIt was the first season where the premier senior teams had competed for the Fox Memorial Shield. Prior to 1931 the trophy awarded was the Monteith Shield, and before that the Myers Cup. The donor of the Monteith Shield wrote to the league asking permission to withdraw the trophy from club competition and that the league play for a new trophy named after [[Edward Vincent Fox]] who had passed away the season previous and who had been heavily involved in [[Auckland Rugby League]] for a long period of time. The new trophy was being donated by friends of Fox.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =A.R.L. Affairs/Fox Memorial Shield/The Games for Saturday\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 100\n| date = 30 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310430.2.181\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> The trophy was finished and presented to the league in September. It was described thus; \"measuring 27 inches across by 22 inches deep, the base is a handsome sample of polished [[rimu]], with overlay of contrasting [[puriri]], on which is an ornate centrepiece in oxidised silver depicting an incident of play in the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] v [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] match of 1926\". The donators of the trophy even went to the extent of sending the silver piece to [[England]] to have it effectively reproduced.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football Trophy/Prize for Club Champions\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 218\n| date = 15 September 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310915.2.122\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Fox Memorial Shield was won by [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]] who defeated [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] 12\u20135 in the final round to win the competition by 3 competition points over the same side. [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] did however win the Roope Rooster competition defeating [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] in the final, and they beat [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]] to win the Stormont Trophy. Alongside these feats [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] also won the inaugural reserve grade competition with a 5\u20135 draw in the final securing them the 1 competition point they needed. [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]] won the Stallard Cup by winning the reserve grade knockout competition. On the final day of the season Mr. Samuel Harris of the [[Newton Rangers]] team had a heart attack while running with the ball in the final of the Seven-A-Side charity tournament. The game was called off with no result given. He had played with Newton for 2 seasons after moving to [[Auckland]] from [[Hikurangi]]. He was single and 26 years of age.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Tragedy/League Player Collapses/Death at Carlaw Park\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 259\n| date = 2 November 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19311102.2.89\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Auckland Council|Auckland City Council]] Parks Committee designated the following of its grounds to the league code: [[Auckland Domain]] (2), Outer Domain (1), [[Victoria Park, Auckland]] (1), Walker Road (2), [[Western Springs]] (1), Grey Lynn Park (1), and 1 additional ground at [[Grey Lynn]] to alternate between rugby and league.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =General Sports News\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20854\n| date = 22 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310422.2.169.7\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Financial statement and annual report ==\nThe annual report to be filed at the annual general meeting showed that the league had a \u00a39,711 5/9 surplus with total assets of \u00a310,534 19/4. As there were smaller crowds in 1930 the gate receipts were \u00a32,282 12/, down from \u00a33,465 10/5 in 1929. The Junior Management Committee reported that the number of juniors registered was 1,930 compared with 984 the previous year, and 63 teams took the field.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Optimistic Annual Report/Reduced Working Profit\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 85\n| date = 11 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310411.2.152\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> At the annual general meeting Mr. James Carlaw said that \"this is a very important meeting, as we have now reached our twenty-first birthday, and have developed from childhood to manhood\". [[Ted Phelan|Mr. Phelan]] presented trophies to the various winners from the previous season.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Coming of Age/Auckland Rugby League/Bright Future Predicted/Prospects Under New Policy\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 90\n| date = 17 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310417.2.129\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> At the [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] annual meeting Mr. A. Ferguson who was a member of the New Zealand Council and who was presiding over the meeting said that the league game in [[New Zealand]] needed to follow the Australian model. He stated that they \"demonstrated the value of physical fitness, which was produced by intensive, scientific training\".<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Question of Status/Suggestion by Official\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 76\n| date = 31 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310331.2.139\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Senior competition restructuring and Carlaw Park gate takings ==\nAn early key development was that a management committee meeting which also included the special committee setup the previous year to look into the restructuring of the Senior A and Senior B competitions adjusted their plans. It had been decided at the end of the 1930 season to reduce the Senior A competition from eight teams to six, thus forcing teams into mergers. This was adjusted to seven teams after this meeting. The teams would be [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]], [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]], [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]-[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] (which also included the Mangere club, who could then choose their own name),<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Ellerslie-Otahuhu United League Football Club\n| page =20\n| work =Auckland Star| volume= LXII| issue= 74\n| date = 28 March 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310328.2.188.5\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]], [[City Rovers|,City]] [[Newton Rangers|Newton]], and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]. The Kingsland team which had been removed from the A grade asked for permission to join with the [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]].\n\nThe B grade (essentially the second division which had run from 1925\u20131930) was still to be eliminated. The league would encourage B grade players to try out for the reserve grade teams in the A grade clubs.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Seven Senior Teams/Rugby League Proposals/Original Plan Dropped/Resolution Carried Unanimously\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]], Auckland Star| volume= LXII| issue= 36, 12 February 1931\n| date = 12 February 1930\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310212.2.159\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a major development for the rugby league game in [[Auckland]] the special committee recommended that winning teams would be granted 12.5% of the net gate takings each weekend with losing teams sharing a \"trifle less\". The league would also enforce a rule where every Senior A club must field a reserve grade team \"of sufficient calibre to satisfy the management committee\". If they failed to do so they would be vulnerable to being removed from the A grade. The league also reserved the right to set the two lowest teams together at the end of the season against each other in a match and eliminating the losers, or compelling them to improve their standard of play or withdraw from the league.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Clubs a Fifth\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 55\n| date = 6 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310306.2.143\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Eastern Suburbs Tour of New Zealand ==\nIn mid October the Eastern Suburbs club team from Sydney toured New Zealand. They played three matches at Carlaw Park against Devonport, a comined Marist-Devonport team, and an Auckland colts side.\n\n== Rule changes ==\nAt the Management Committee meeting prior to the start of the season it was decided to adhere to the latest rules, where a team forcing the ball in their own in goal area would take a drop kick from the 25-yard line as opposed from their own try line. There was an adjustment to the weight allowance from the fourth grade down, and sixth grade players should be under 18 and a half on 1 May.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Management Committee/New Drop-Out Rule Adopted\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 90\n| date = 17 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310417.2.129\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> At a following Management Committee meeting it was reported that the English Rugby League had advised that at scrum put in's the loose head would be transferred from the defending team to the attacking team.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Management Meeting\n| page = 17\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 95\n| date = 23 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310423.2.157\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August a referee was assaulted by a player after a match between the [[City Rovers|City]] and Newmarket Fourth Grade teams at [[Western Springs]]. He had ordered off a player from each team. The City player came back on the field and his team refused to remove him so the referee called the match off. He was then harassed by a number of players and one of them then fought with him, \"the pair rolled on the ground fighting for a few minutes, the referee holding his own until some spectators intervened and separated\" them.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Referee Assaulted/League Football Incident\n| page = 15\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20955\n| date = 19 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310819.2.160.1\n| accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== New clubs at Papakura and Glenora, and several amalgamations ==\nOn 26 March the [[Papakura Sea Eagles|Papakura Rugby League club]] was formed with 60 players enrolling.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papakura Club Formed\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20828\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310321.2.141.4\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> They applied to the Papakura Town Board for use of the reserve at [[Papakura]]. This was granted as the entire club had switched over from the Rugby Union game thereby meaning they had no competition for the field. The council said that if a representative rugby game was being played on the field then the league team could use Prince Edward Park (which later became their home ground and remains so to this day).<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papakura Town Board\n| page = 5\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 70\n| date = 24 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310324.2.51\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> On Saturday, 18 April they played a practice match with Mount Wellington at [[Papakura]] at 3pm.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football/Mount Wellington Rugby League Club\n| page = 6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20851\n| date = 18 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310418.2.8.2\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> The match was won by Mount Wellington by 8 points to 5. Papakura's points came from an unconverted try to Johnstone, and I. Wilson kicked a penalty goal.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Several Practices Held\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20852\n| date = 20 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310420.2.136.12\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> They held their first social on the evening of Wednesday 22 April at the Paragon Theatre.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Social Gatherings\n| page = 10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 97\n| date = 27 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310427.2.127.2\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Kingsland club amalgamated with the [[Marist Saints|Marist]] club which meant that their senior players would be joining those of [[Marist Saints|Marist]]. This placed [[Marist Saints|Marist]] as one of the early favourites to win the Senior Grade. This was discussed in an article on the prospects of all the teams in the New Zealand Herald.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The League Code/Prospects for New Season/Better Standard Expected/Strength of Various Clubs\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20859\n| date = 29 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310429.2.151.3\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]], [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]], and Mangere clubs combined to form a senior team with the Mangere Senior B team being regraded to first junior with the team to play as part of the Ellerslie-Otahuhu side.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Protest by Richmond/A Decision Postponed/Reserve Grade Principle\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 106\n| date = 7 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310507.2.178\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref> However [[Mangere Rugby League Football Club]] then sent a deputation to a Management Committee meeting asking to be able to play as a separate institution as a junior club rather than be a part of the Ellerslie-Otahuhu amalgamation.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 112\n| date = 14 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310514.2.142\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref> They wished to be affiliated to the league under their own name rather than amalgamate with [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]. Several speakers were heard by the league and they said that they wished to play league football but maintain their own identity as a M\u0101ori team. The League said that there should be a conference with [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] and in the meantime they would play for one week with [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Request from Mangere Club\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20872\n| date = 14 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310514.2.30.3\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref> At a league meeting on 27 May the league decided to uphold their earlier ruling and enforce the amalgamation with the decision reviewed at the end of the season. It was expressed that the Mangere players were willing to play as the league suggested. Mr. [[Jim Rukutai]] suggested that Mangere be granted permission to retain their identity for twelve months, subject to all transfers being through the Ellerslie-Otahuhu United Club. The chairman of the league said \"he did not think that there was any objection to Mangere playing as the Mangere section of the amalgamated club, but it was the duty of the League to uphold Ellerslie-Otahuhu Club\". In the meantime he thought \"moral suasion should be used by the members and the position would right itself\".<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Management Meeting/Ellerslie-Mangere Position\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 124\n| date = 28 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310528.2.178\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref> At the Management Committee meeting on 10 June it was reported by the chairman that the Mangere and [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] clubs had reached a satisfactory agreement and that \"the M\u0101ori senior team,\u2026 was willing to continue playing the league code. It was intended that Mangere should apply for the resignation of its players who had already played for Ellerslie\" The matter would be deferred for one week.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Ellerslie-Mangere Dispute\n| page = 7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20896\n| date = 11 June 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310611.2.28.5\n| accessdate = 23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced at a [[City Rovers]] club meeting that the Parnell club had amalgamated with them. They would enter teams in the senior, reserve senior, first junior, third intermediate, fourth, fifth, sixth, and seventh grades, and also in the primary school competition.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =City Club Meetings\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 97\n| date = 27 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310427.2.129.15\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> Ten of the Parnell senior B players were regraded to first class juniors and would play for that particular [[City Rovers]] side.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Protest by Richmond/A Decision Postponed/Reserve Grade Principle\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 106\n| date = 7 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310507.2.178\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June a new club was registered in the [[Glen Eden, New Zealand|Glen Eden]] district and was named [[Glenora Bears|Glenora]]. They would enter a team in the third grade intermediate.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Junior Management/New Club Accepted\n| page = 12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 129\n| date = 3 June 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310603.2.139\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n  {{s-bef|before=[[1930 Auckland Rugby League season|1930]]}}\n  {{s-ttl|title=23rd [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n  |years=1931}}\n  {{s-aft|after=[[1932 Auckland Rugby League season|1932]]}}\n  {{end}}\n\n== Senior grade competitions ==\nThe Senior Grade was reduced from 8 teams to 7 for the 1931 season. Each team had to field a reserve side and their matches were to be played prior to the A team's matches at the same venue.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brighter League/The 1931 Kick-Off/Carlaw Park Matches/Shore and City Featured\n| page =13\n| work =Auckland Star| volume= LXII| issue= 101\n| date = 1 April 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310501.2.130\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Senior A grade standings ===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]\n|12||11||0||1||204||88||'''23'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]]\n|12||10||0||2||180||92||'''20'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]]\n|12||7||1||4||143||93||'''15'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|12||6||1||5||152||143||'''13'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|12||2||2||8||83||147||'''6'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|12||2||1||9||132||179||'''5'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie-Otahuhu United]]\n|12||1||1||10||85||237||'''3'''\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Senior A Grade Fixtures ===\nIn Round 1 [[Marist Saints|Marist]] won after time however the play was continued erroneously. Time was up but the time keeper allowed additional tackles and did not ring the bell until after the winning try had been scored.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Match Won After Time\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 104\n| date = 5 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310505.2.120\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] protested the result and after multiple meetings it was eventually decided by the league Management Committee to replay the match.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Richmond Club Protest\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 112\n| date = 14 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310514.2.142\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Round 3 match between [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] and [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] was the first ever senior league match played at [[Western Springs Stadium]] which had opened for cycling and field sports in 1929.\n\nThe Round 12 match at [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] between the hosts and Ellerslie-Otahuhu was one with paid entry after permission was granted by the Devonport Borough Council. A sum of \u00a312 5/ was raised to assist the Devonport Welfare League's funds.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Gate-Takings at Devonport\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 175\n| date = 27 July 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310727.2.125\n| accessdate = 24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Round 13 matches were played in terrible conditions which saw the cancellation of almost all league in Auckland. The Ellerslie-Otahuhu v [[Marist Saints|Marist]] match played at [[Papatoetoe]] was abandoned at halftime with the result 21\u20133 in favour of [[Marist Saints|Marist]] standing as the final score.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1931 Senior A Grade Results\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Round 1\n| 2 May<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Kick Off/Devonport Downs City/Marist Just Gets Home/Ellerslie and Newton Draw\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume= LXII| issue= 103\n| date = 4 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310504.2.131\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n|| Devonport || 23 || City || 18 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \u2013\n| 2 May || Marist || 11 || Richmond || 10 || Carlaw Park # 2, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \u2013\n| 2 May || Ellerslie-Otahuhu || 5 || Newton || 5 || Ellerslie, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Round 2\n| 9 May<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Senior Grade Contests/Marist Defeats Ponsonby/Easy Win for Devonport\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20869\n| date = 11 M