lose League Match/Success of Combined Team/Victory by Single Point/Eastern Suburbs Defeated\n| page =9\n| work =New Zealand Herald| volume= LXVIII| issue= 21007\n| date = 19 October 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19311019.2.136\n| accessdate = 28 September 2019}}</ref>\n|| Devonport-Marist Combined|| 14 || Eastern Suburbs (Sydney) || 13 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3:15pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Eastern Suburbs Tour Match\n| 21 Oct<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Finale/Eastern Suburbs Win Again/Clever Play by Rearguard/Auckland Colts Go Well\n| page =16\n| work =Auckland Star| volume= LXII| issue= 250\n| date = 22 October 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19311022.2.149\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|| Auckland Colts|| 13 || Eastern Suburbs (Sydney) || 18 || Carlaw Park # 1, 4pm\n|-\n|}\n\n== Representative season ==\nIt was a very quiet year on the representative team front. There was a match played between North Island and South Island, but the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team's only match was for the Northern Union Cup against [[Northland rugby league team|Northland]]. In a surprise result Northland had defeated [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] to lift the trophy. [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] challenged for it but could only manage a 19 all draw and so Northland retained it. Auckland junior teams played two matches and a colts side played against the touring [[Sydney Roosters|Eastern Suburbs]] team from [[Sydney]] who were the premiers of the [[New South Wales Rugby League]].\n\n=== Representative fixtures ===\nOnly a small number of fixtures were played in the 1931 season partly owing to the fact that [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] did not hold the Northern Union Cup. Also the touring [[Sydney Roosters|Eastern Suburbs]] team from Sydney had matches with club sides organised for them.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1931 Auckland Representative Fixtures\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Representative Fixture\n| 15 Aug<ref>{{cite news\n| title =High Scoring Game/North Island League Team/Too Superior for South/Margin of Twenty-Nine Points\n| page = 11\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20953\n| date = 17 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310817.2.130\n| accessdate = 26 October 2019}}</ref>\n|| North Island || 52 || South Island || 23 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Northern Union Cup\n| 26 Sep<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Fixture/Auckland and Northland/Match Ends in a Draw\n| page = 10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume= LXVIII| issue= 20989\n| date = 28 September 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310928.2.131.5\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 19 || Northland || 19 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3:15pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Representative Match\n| 17 Oct<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Wednesday Reps V Junior Reps\n| page =9\n| work =New Zealand Herald| volume= LXVIII| issue= 21007\n| date = 19 October 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19311019.2.136\n| accessdate = 28 September 2019}}</ref>\n|| Wednesday Representatives|| 23 || Auckland Junior Representatives || 6 || Carlaw Park\n|-\n|}\n\n== Annual general meetings and club news ==\n*[[Auckland Rugby League]] held their annual general meeting in the Chamber of Commerce, Swanson Street on Thursday 16 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=82\n| date = 8 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310408.2.172.3\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> At a later meeting they voted to adopt the motion whereby its grading of referees and appointments of them for matches would be done by a group of three, consisting of two of its members and a representative of the [[Auckland Rugby League]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Appointment of Referees/Management Representation Approved\n| page = 12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=98\n| date = 28 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310428.2.125\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> Tenders were requested for the lease of the Carlaw Park Refreshment Stall, and for the rights of the Rugby League Gazette.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland Rugby Football League\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=87\n| date = 14 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310414.2.188.3\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Auckland Rugby League]] Junior Management Committee held their annual meeting at the Grey Buildings on Tuesday, 31 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20834\n| date = 28 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310328.2.10.4\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> After the reports were given by club delegates the prospect was for a record season in terms of team and player numbers. Mr. C. Adamson was elected Chairman, with his deputy Mr. W. Lusty.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Lower Grade Prospects\n| page = 15\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20837\n| date = 1 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310401.2.151\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> During the season the Junior Management Committee became dissatisfied with their chairman Mr. C. Adamson because he voted contrarily to their position at an Auckland Rugby League meeting. They subsequently voted him out of the position. Mr. George Rhodes, chairman of the senior management committee attended a later meeting to say that Adamson was on the senior board as an independent representative, not as a representative of the Junior Management Committee and their dismissal of him was unjustified. A vote was then held over who should be chairman with Mr. J. H. Eddowes nominated along with Mr. Adamson and the former won by 10 votes to 6.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Junior Board Trouble/Mediation by Mr. Rhodes/New Chairman Nominated\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 183\n| date = 5 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310805.2.122\n| accessdate = 26 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*Auckland Rugby League Primary School Management Committee\n*[[Auckland Rugby League]] Referees Association annual meeting was held at the League Rooms, Grey Buildings on 30 March. The report stated that membership had increased and the standard of refereeing was maintained at a high level.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Referees Association\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 77\n| date = 2 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310402.2.161\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Akarana Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual general meeting at Carlaw Park on Thursday 9 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20842\n| date = 8 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310408.2.165.5\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Avondale League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Hick's Tearooms, Avondale on Wednesday 25 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 69\n| date = 23 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310323.2.194.2\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> There was an attendance of about twenty players and the cash credit was \u00a37 10/8. The club voted to thank Mr. H. P. Burton for the use of his ground where the majority of their matches were played in 1930.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Avondale Club\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 73\n| date = 27 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310327.2.138.9\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[City Rovers]] annual meeting was held at Carlaw Park on Sunday 22 March to discuss the annual report, balance sheet, general business and to elect officers. Seventy five people attended the meeting where the annual report showed a balance of \u00a333 10/6. They stated that their chances of winning the title the year before was spoiled by the fact that they lost four players to the New Zealand team which toured Australia. They were aiming to have teams in all of the junior grades.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Annual Meetings Held/The City Club\u2019s Season\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20832\n| date = 26 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310326.2.34.7\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Devonport United Football Club]] annual general meeting was held in the Labour Rooms (above Hellaby's), Devonport on Monday 30 March regarding the election of officers and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20830\n| date = 24 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310324.2.158.8\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> About fifty members attended and the balance sheet showed a credit of \u00a39 7/2.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Question of Status/Suggestion by Official\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 76\n| date = 31 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310331.2.139\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie United League Football Club]] held their annual general meeting at the Club's Training Shed, Ellerslie on Monday 23 March. They requested that everybody attend as it would be their final meeting due to the league enforced merger with Otahuhu.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 68\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310321.2.177.1\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*Ellerslie-Otahuhu United League Football Club held their first general meeting at the Ellerslie club's training shed opposite the railway station on Monday 30 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page =20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 74\n| date = 28 March 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310328.2.188.5\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They had practice for all grades on Saturday 18 April to make final arrangements for all teams as there was a merger of Ellerslie, Otahuhu and Mangere.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 90\n| date = 17 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310417.2.156.1\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Glen Lynn League Football Club]] held their annual general meeting at the Delta Theatre on Monday 23 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=67\n| date = 20 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310320.2.129.4\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> The Glen Lynn club wrote a letter to the New Lynn Borough Council asking for assistance in acquiring a playing area. The council intended to give the club details of an existing league football area on Great North Road in New Lynn which had been used by the New Lynn club prior to the joining of New Lynn and Glen Eden.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local Bodies/New Lynn Borough Council\n| page = 5\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 70\n| date = 24 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310324.2.48\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Kingsland Athletic Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Liberty Luncheon Rooms at the top of Symonds Street on Monday 30 March to discuss the annual report and balance sheet.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 68\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310321.2.177.1\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They held a further Special General Meeting on Thursday 16 April at Donovan's Gym, Parnell with all juniors requested to roll up.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 87\n| date = 14 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310414.2.188.8\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> The Kingsland club amalgamated with the Marist club after they lost Senior A grade status.\n\n*[[Marist Saints|Marist Brothers Old Boys League Football Club]] annual meeting held at Donovan's Gymnasium, Parnell on Monday 30 March.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20834\n| date = 28 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310328.2.10.4\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mangere Rugby League Football Club]] held a meeting in the Strand Theatre Hall, Onehunga on Wednesday, 29 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 18\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20859\n| date = 29 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310429.2.160.8\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mt Albert Lions|Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the King George Hall in [[Mount Albert, New Zealand|Mount Albert]] on Thursday, 5 March to discuss the annual report, balance sheet, election of officers, and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20812\n| date = 3 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310303.2.159.7\n| accessdate = 2 October 2019}}</ref> There first practice was held at the club's grounds on Springleigh Avenue on Saturday, 11 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 83\n| date = 9 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310409.2.218.4\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> At a Management Committee meeting on 22 April Mount Albert applied to have its Senior B team (who had played in the Senior B Grade \u2013 effectively the 2nd division of senior teams in 1930) regraded to first junior.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Management Meeting\n| page = 17\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 95\n| date = 23 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310423.2.157\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mt Wellington Rugby League Football Club]] annual meeting was held at the Abattoir, Westfield on Tuesday 24 March to discuss the annual report and balance sheet, the election of officers, and general business. Players and intending players were requested to attend.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20826\n| date = 19 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310319.2.173.3\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Newmarket Rugby League Football Club]] annual meeting was held at the Club Room 235, Khyber Pass, Thursday 26 March. All players and intending players were invited to attend.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue=44\n| date = 21 February 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310221.2.162.3\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Newton Rangers]] Football Club annual meeting was held at the Y.M.C.A on Wellesley St. East on Monday 23 March. All vice presidents, members and intending members were invited to attend including late Senior B players (players from Senior B clubs who no longer had senior teams).<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue=20822\n| date = 14 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310314.2.8.2\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> There was a large attendance with Mr. W. Badley presiding over the meeting and Mr. W. Monteith was elected patron<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Newton Club\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20832\n| date = 26 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310326.2.34.7\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>..\n\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers Football Club]] annual general meeting was held at the Foresters' Hall, Birkenhead on Thursday 12 March to discuss \"business important\".<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20818\n| date = 10 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310310.2.172.4\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> They donated \u00a32 2s to the Mayors fund for Napier Earthquake fund.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Mayor\u2019s Fund/Further Contributions/Total of \u00a322,969 to Date\n| page = 11\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20818\n| date = 10 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310310.2.120\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> The annual meeting of the [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers Football Club]] was their 21st. The president of the club was Mr. A. E. Greenslade who was also the mayor of Northcote. The club report stated that they had a membership of 115 and fielded six teams in the league competition, and that this made them the fourth largest club in [[Auckland]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers\n| page =13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 61\n| date = 13 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310313.2.157.5\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu Rugby League Football Club]] were given use of the Sturges Park and Princes Street playing grounds in a shared arrangement with rugby by the Otahuhu Borough Council.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Otahuhu Borough Council\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 84\n| date = 10 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310410.2.24\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Papakura Sea Eagles|Papakura Rugby League Football Club]] The Papakura Rugby Club had decided to disband and play league instead.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Manukau Union\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20829\n| date = 23 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310323.2.163.9\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They held their first ever meeting in the Parish Hall, Papakura on Thursday, 26 March. Officials of the [[Auckland Rugby League]] were present. All members, intending members, players and supporters were invited to attend.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20828\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310321.2.10.1\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> Following the meeting a club was formed with 60 players enrolling.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papakura Club Formed\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20828\n| date = 21 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310321.2.141.4\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Papatoetoe Rugby League Club]] held their annual meeting in mid April. There was a large attendance and it was decided to nominate five teams for the season, namely third grade open, fourth grade, fifth grade, sixth grade, and a schoolboys.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papatoetoe Club\u2019s Meeting\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 90\n| date = 17 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310417.2.136\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> The club held its annual ball in the Papatoetoe Town Hall on 24 July. The venue was decorated in the club's colours of blue and gold.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Papatoetoe Dance\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 174\n| date = 25 July 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310725.2.134.3\n| accessdate = 24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Sailing Club's Hall on Thursday 19 March to discuss business, balance-sheet, and election of officers.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 65\n| date = 18 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310318.2.190.3\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Leys Institute, Ponsonby on Monday 30 March to receive their annual report and balance sheet, elect officers, and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 22\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20831\n| date = 25 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310325.2.180.5\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> 80 members attended the meeting and the report referred to how successful the club had been, especially with the senior side winning the Monteith Shield, Roope Rooster, and Thistle Cup. The third grade open team was particularly good and the schoolboy team consisted of players from Ponsonby, Curran Street, and Bayfield Schools.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Referees Association/Ponsonby Club\u2019s Meeting\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 77\n| date = 2 April 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310402.2.161\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers Football Club]] annual meeting was held in the Gaiety Hall, Surrey Crescent on Friday 20 March to discuss the annual report and statement of accounts, and general business.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 59\n| date = 11 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310311.2.187.7\n| accessdate = 17 October 2019}}</ref> About 100 members were in attendance. The report showed that the club had fielded 12 teams in 1930 with four winning the championship. Trophies were presented as follows \u2013 Lauder Cup, fourth grade; Milicich Cup, seventh grade A team; Walker Shield: second grade; and a trophy to the schoolboys who tied for first place.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Richmond Club\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume= LXVIII |issue= 20832\n| date = 26 March 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19310326.2.34.7\n| accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref> They held an additional meeting for all prospective Senior, Senior B, and Second Grade players at Grey Lynn Park on Wednesday, 8 April.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football\n| page = 24\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 77\n| date = 2 April 1931\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310402.2.171.6\n| accessdate = 21 October 2019}}</ref> On 16 May the Richmond club performed the notable feat of having all eight of its A teams winning their matches, although its Seventh Grade B team was defeated, and the 5th Grade team's victory was by default.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Manukau and Richmond\n| page = 12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 115\n| date = 18 May 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310518.2.142.11\n| accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season the Third Grade captain for [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]], Mr. George Williams drowned in a fishing accident in Breaker Bay, Wellington.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Three Drowned/Wellington Tragedy/Small Fishing Boat Lost/Story Told by Survivor/Wrecked on Submerged Rock\n| page = 7\n| work = [[Auckland Star]] | volume=LXII| issue=97\n| date = 27 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310427.2.83\n| accessdate = 23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Junior Management Affairs\n| page = 10\n| work = [[Auckland Star]] |volume= LXII |issue= 201\n| date = 26 August 1931\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19310826.2.125\n| accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:1931 in New Zealand rugby league|Auckland Rugby League]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1931_Auckland_Rugby_League_season"}
{"title_page": "Oerlikon KBA", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox weapon|name = Oerlikon KBA 25 mm\n|image =[[Image:OTO_KBA.jpg|280px]] \n|caption = Oerlikon KBA 25 mm automatic cannon (Remote controlled weapon station)\n|origin =Italy\n|type = [[Autocannon]] \n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged = yes\n|is_artillery = yes \n<!-- Service history -->\n|service = Mid 1970s \u2013 present\n|used_by = See ''[[#Operators|operators]]''\n|designer = [[Oerlikon Contraves AG]]\n|design_date =\n|manufacturer = [[Rheinmetall Air Defence]];<br>[[Ford Motor Company]] (designated KBA-B02 under license agreement with Oerlikon and [[TRW Inc.]] as a competitor to Hughes' Bushmaster)<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015074749436;view=1up;seq=218 Fiscal Year 1977 Authorization for Military Procurement], pt.6, p. 3268.</ref>\n|unit_cost =\n|production_date =\n|number = 4,000+\n|variants = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n|spec_label =\n|weight = {{convert|112|kg|abbr=on}}\n|part_length = Overall: {{convert|2.888|m|abbr=on}}\n|width = {{convert|263|mm|abbr=on}}\n|height = {{convert|283|mm|abbr=on}}\n|diameter =\n|crew =\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge = [[25 mm caliber|NATO 25\u00d7137mm]]\n|caliber = 25 mm\n|barrels = \n|action =\n|rate = Nominal: 600 rounds/min, Maximum: 700 rounds/min\n|velocity = {{convert|1400|m/s|abbr=on}}\n|range = {{convert|3020|m|abbr=on}}\n|feed =\n|sights =\n|max_range={{convert|5850|m|abbr=on}}\n}}\n[[File:Oerlikon KBA.JPG|thumb|OTO Melara 25/80 with Oerlikon KBA]]\nThe '''Oerlikon KBA''' is a [[25 mm caliber|25 mm (25\u00d7137mm)]] autocannon, developed as a close range weapon for the mechanized battlefield originally made by Oerlikon Contraves AG (renamed as [[Rheinmetall Air Defence]] AG following the merger with [[Rheinmetall]] in 2009).\n\nThe Oerlikon KBA is a gas operated selective fire weapon taking a 25&nbsp;mm cartridge from a dual selective belt feed and firing at a rate of 600 rounds per minute, it has been developed as a close-range multipurpose weapon for the modern battlefield.\n\nDue to its firepower, various types of ammunition and its \"Instant Ammunition Selection Device\" (IASD), the KBA can engage lightly armoured vehicles, infantry and anti-tank positions, helicopters, combat aircraft and ships.\n\n== Description ==\nThe Oerlikon KBA 25&nbsp;mm cannon is a fully automatic, positively locked, gas-operated weapon with a rotating bolt head and double belt feed. These features guarantee high reliability and safety, even under the most extreme environmental conditions.\n\nThe KBA offers a wide range of firing modes: single shot; programmable rapid single shot with a rate of fire of up to 200 rds/min; and full automatic fire of 600 rds/ min. The cannon functions, such as cocking and firing, are electrically actuated by remote control unit or in auxiliary mode mechanically by a hand crank and a trigger pedal.\n\nThe Oerlikon KBA 25mm cannon has been designed for integration in various types of mounts, small size and low weight offer various integration possibilities such as: \n* Manned (1 or 2 operators) or remote controlled turrets on IFVs, APCs\n* Air defence gun mounts\n* Naval mounts\n* Helicopter mounts\n\nThe various types of available ammunition combined with the unique Instant Ammunition Selection Device (IASD) and different selectable firing modes with a rate of fire up to 600rds/min support any type of operational use.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1964 the American company [[TRW Inc.]] was entrusted with the development of a 25&nbsp;mm weapon while Oerlikon-Buehrle Machine Tool Works assumed responsibility for developing the ammunition and interior ballistics for it.\n\nBoth were intended to meet the requirements for the armament of [[infantry fighting vehicle]]s of the 80's and 90's: \n* Ammunition performance: 25&nbsp;mm armour steel, 60\u00b0 (NATO) angle of impact, 1000m range, corresponding to the armour of a well-armoured infantry fighting vehicle.\n* \"Instant ammunition selection\" for engagement of different targets\n* Selectable firing mode: Accurate single shot, bursts with a rate of fire of more than 550 rds/min for engagement of aircraft\n* Compact structure: with low weight for installation in gun turrets of APC's\n* Simple to operate: and service in the hands of infantry\n\n[[File:KBA Draw.png|left|thumb|284x284px|Oerlikon KBA 25mm Part Description]]\nThree years later, at the beginning of 1967, technical tests and firing trials were carried out with the first two American prototype (recoil operated) cannons (TRW-6425)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bevfitchett.us/machine-gun-v5/mm-trw-automatic-cannon.html|title=Mm Trw Automatic Cannon - Machine Gun V5|website=www.bevfitchett.us|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref> at Oerlikon-Buehrle Machine Tool Works followed by the first demonstrations for another NATO country.\n\nIn the trials, however, the American prototypes displayed a number of basic functional deficiencies. This persuaded Oerlikon-Buehrle Machine Tool Works to undertake their own development work to effect system modifications, which then resulted in the required functional reliability and enabled the trials to be completed successfully. (1970, 10 gas-operated cannons). When the first prototype cannons became available, suitable gun turrets had also to be provided. In 1967 an agreement was signed between Machine Tool Works Oerlikon-Buehrle and a well-known and established sub-contractor, to collaborate in the development and manufacture of 25&nbsp;mm gun turrets. These gun turrets were in the first instance to be suitable for mounting on [[M113 armoured personnel carrier]] C&R of a NATO country's army. \nThe complete system, cannon, hand-driven turret and ammunition underwent detailed firing trials between 1969 and 1971. Special new development efforts were devoted to improve functional reliability, durability and firing precision, and in 1971 sufficient progress had been made for the weapon system to fulfil the strict specifications laid down, and to be delivered to the Netherlands.\n\nWithin the framework of the product support service Oerlikon improves the product and adapts it regularly to the latest requirements. An important step forward was made in 1982/83 when the ammunition penetration performance range of the 25&nbsp;mm APDS-T (sub-caliber) round was increased 150% from 1000 to 2500 m.\n\nThe wide range of strong points of the Oerlikon KBA 25&nbsp;mm cannon, such as high rate of fire, ammunition performance, good safety record, dual belt feeder with first-round response, no external power requirement and simple maintenance lead to a considerably increasing interest in the Oerlikon KBA 25&nbsp;mm cannon in years.\n\n== Ammunition ==\nA wide range of ammunition has been developed for this weapon specifically developed to engage and defeat both ground and air targets.\n\nThe ammunition complies with all handling and operational safety requirements according to MIL-STD\u2019s, and was subjected to intensive trials by NATO member countries prior to its introduction and standardization as NATO 25mmx137 ammunition.\n[[File:US Navy 090129-N-4774B-008 Gunner's Mate 2nd Class Nicholas Brassard inspects rounds for the MK-38 25mm machine gun system.jpg|thumb|US Navy gunner inspects TP-T rounds]]\nThe current 25mm ammunition family consists of six combat and two training rounds:\n* [[Armour-piercing fin-stabilized discarding-sabot|APFSDS-T]]: armour-piercing fin stabilized discarding sabot with tracer, for use against armoured ground targets\n* [[Armour-piercing discarding sabot|APDS-T]]: armour-piercing discarding sabot with tracer, for use against armoured ground targets\n* FAPDS-T: frangible armour-piercing discarding sabot with tracer, for use against air, ground and urban targets\n* TPDS-T: target practice discarding sabot with tracer, a short range trainer for the above sub-calibre types\n* [[Semi-armor-piercing high-explosive incendiary|SAPHEI]]-T: semi-armour-piercing high explosive incendiary with tracer, for use against well protected targets\n* [[High-explosive incendiary|HEI]]-T: high explosive incendiary with tracer, for use against lightly protected targets\n* MP-T: multipurpose with tracer\n* TP-T: target practice with tracer, for training with the above full calibre types\n\n== Operators ==\n\n=== Current operators ===\n[[File:VBM Freccia visto frontalmente.JPG|thumb|Example of KBA gun installed on Italian 8x8 [[Freccia IFV|Freccia]] wheeled Infantry fighting vehicle in use with the Italian Army.]]\n*{{Flag|Bangladesh}}\n** [[Minerva-class corvette|Leader Class offshore patrol vessel]]\n** [[Sobuj Bangla-class patrol craft|''Sobuj Bangla''-class inshore patrol vessel]]\n* {{TUR}}\n** ASELSAN 25&nbsp;mm STOP Stabilized Naval Gun System<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/year-2015-news/july-2015-navy-naval-forces-defense-industry-technology-maritime-security-global-news/2935-aselsan-stop-25mm-remote-weapon-stations-for-pakistan-navy-fleet-tanker-project.html|title=Aselsan STOP 25mm Remote Weapon Stations for Pakistan Navy Fleet Tanker Project|work=Navy Recognition|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Egypt}}\n* {{ITA}}\n** [[FREMM]] multipurpose frigate\n** [[Italian aircraft carrier Cavour|CVH 550 ''Cavour'']] aircraft carrier\n** [[Freccia IFV|VBM Freccia infantry fighting vehicle]]\n** [[SIDAM 25]] self-propelled anti-aircraft gun\n** [[Horizon-class frigate]]\n* {{Flag|Japan}}\n** [[Type 87 ARV]]\n* {{Flag|Netherlands}}\n* {{Flag|Chile}}\n* {{Flag|Romania}}\n** [[MLI-84]] tracked infantry fighting vehicle\n* {{Flag|Bahrain}}\n* {{Flag|Turkmenistan}}\n*{{Flag|Malta}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Oerlikon-Contraves]]\n[[Category:Autocannon]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox weapon|name = Oerlikon KBA 25 mm\n|image =[[Image:OTO_KBA.jpg|280px]] \n|caption = Oerlikon KBA 25 mm automatic cannon (Remote controlled weapon station)\n|origin =Italy\n|type = [[Autocannon]] \n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged = yes\n|is_artillery = yes \n<!-- Service history -->\n|service = Mid 1970s \u2013 present\n|used_by = See ''[[#Operators|operators]]''\n|designer = [[Oerlikon Contraves AG]]\n|design_date =\n|manufacturer = [[Rheinmetall Air Defence]];<br>[[Ford Motor Company]] (designated KBA-B02 under license agreement with Oerlikon and [[TRW Inc.]] as a competitor to Hughes' Bushmaster)<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015074749436;view=1up;seq=218 Fiscal Year 1977 Authorization for Military Procurement], pt.6, p. 3268.</ref>\n|unit_cost =\n|production_date =\n|number = 4,000+\n|variants = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n|spec_label =\n|weight = {{convert|112|kg|abbr=on}}\n|part_length = Overall: {{convert|2.888|m|abbr=on}}\n|width = {{convert|263|mm|abbr=on}}\n|height = {{convert|283|mm|abbr=on}}\n|diameter =\n|crew =\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge = [[25 mm caliber|NATO 25\u00d7137mm]]\n|caliber = 25 mm\n|barrels = \n|action =\n|rate = Nominal: 600 rounds/min, Maximum: 700 rounds/min\n|velocity = {{convert|1400|m/s|abbr=on}}\n|range = {{convert|3020|m|abbr=on}}\n|feed =\n|sights =\n|max_range={{convert|5850|m|abbr=on}}\n}}\n[[File:Oerlikon KBA.JPG|thumb|OTO Melara 25/80 with Oerlikon KBA]]\nThe '''Oerlikon KBA''' is a [[25 mm caliber|25 mm (25\u00d7137mm)]] autocannon, developed as a close range weapon for the mechanized battlefield originally made by Oerlikon Contraves AG (renamed as [[Rheinmetall Air Defence]] AG following the merger with [[Rheinmetall]] in 2009).\n\nThe Oerlikon KBA is a gas operated selective fire weapon taking a 25&nbsp;mm cartridge from a dual selective belt feed and firing at a rate of 600 rounds per minute, it has been developed as a close-range multipurpose weapon for the modern battlefield.\n\nDue to its firepower, various types of ammunition and its \"Instant Ammunition Selection Device\" (IASD), the KBA can engage lightly armoured vehicles, infantry and anti-tank positions, helicopters, combat aircraft and ships.\n\n== Description ==\nThe Oerlikon KBA 25&nbsp;mm cannon is a fully automatic, positively locked, gas-operated weapon with a rotating bolt head and double belt feed. These features guarantee high reliability and safety, even under the most extreme environmental conditions.\n\nThe KBA offers a wide range of firing modes: single shot; programmable rapid single shot with a rate of fire of up to 200 rds/min; and full automatic fire of 600 rds/ min. The cannon functions, such as cocking and firing, are electrically actuated by remote control unit or in auxiliary mode mechanically by a hand crank and a trigger pedal.\n\nThe Oerlikon KBA 25mm cannon has been designed for integration in various types of mounts, small size and low weight offer various integration possibilities such as: \n* Manned (1 or 2 operators) or remote controlled turrets on IFVs, APCs\n* Air defence gun mounts\n* Naval mounts\n* Helicopter mounts\n\nThe various types of available ammunition combined with the unique Instant Ammunition Selection Device (IASD) and different selectable firing modes with a rate of fire up to 600rds/min support any type of operational use.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1964 the American company [[TRW Inc.]] was entrusted with the development of a 25&nbsp;mm weapon while Oerlikon-Buehrle Machine Tool Works assumed responsibility for developing the ammunition and interior ballistics for it.\n\nBoth were intended to meet the requirements for the armament of [[infantry fighting vehicle]]s of the 80's and 90's: \n* Ammunition performance: 25&nbsp;mm armour steel, 60\u00b0 (NATO) angle of impact, 1000m range, corresponding to the armour of a well-armoured infantry fighting vehicle.\n* \"Instant ammunition selection\" for engagement of different targets\n* Selectable firing mode: Accurate single shot, bursts with a rate of fire of more than 550 rds/min for engagement of aircraft\n* Compact structure: with low weight for installation in gun turrets of APC's\n* Simple to operate: and service in the hands of infantry\n\nThree years later, at the beginning of 1967, technical tests and firing trials were carried out with the first two American prototype (recoil operated) cannons (TRW-6425)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bevfitchett.us/machine-gun-v5/mm-trw-automatic-cannon.html|title=Mm Trw Automatic Cannon - Machine Gun V5|website=www.bevfitchett.us|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref> at Oerlikon-Buehrle Machine Tool Works followed by the first demonstrations for another NATO country.\n\nIn the trials, however, the American prototypes displayed a number of basic functional deficiencies. This persuaded Oerlikon-Buehrle Machine Tool Works to undertake their own development work to effect system modifications, which then resulted in the required functional reliability and enabled the trials to be completed successfully. (1970, 10 gas-operated cannons). When the first prototype cannons became available, suitable gun turrets had also to be provided. In 1967 an agreement was signed between Machine Tool Works Oerlikon-Buehrle and a well-known and established sub-contractor, to collaborate in the development and manufacture of 25&nbsp;mm gun turrets. These gun turrets were in the first instance to be suitable for mounting on [[M113 armoured personnel carrier]] C&R of a NATO country's army. \nThe complete system, cannon, hand-driven turret and ammunition underwent detailed firing trials between 1969 and 1971. Special new development efforts were devoted to improve functional reliability, durability and firing precision, and in 1971 sufficient progress had been made for the weapon system to fulfil the strict specifications laid down, and to be delivered to the Netherlands.\n\nWithin the framework of the product support service Oerlikon improves the product and adapts it regularly to the latest requirements. An important step forward was made in 1982/83 when the ammunition penetration performance range of the 25&nbsp;mm APDS-T (sub-caliber) round was increased 150% from 1000 to 2500 m.\n\nThe wide range of strong points of the Oerlikon KBA 25&nbsp;mm cannon, such as high rate of fire, ammunition performance, good safety record, dual belt feeder with first-round response, no external power requirement and simple maintenance lead to a considerably increasing interest in the Oerlikon KBA 25&nbsp;mm cannon in years.\n\n== Ammunition ==\nA wide range of ammunition has been developed for this weapon specifically developed to engage and defeat both ground and air targets.\n\nThe ammunition complies with all handling and operational safety requirements according to MIL-STD\u2019s, and was subjected to intensive trials by NATO member countries prior to its introduction and standardization as NATO 25mmx137 ammunition.\n[[File:US Navy 090129-N-4774B-008 Gunner's Mate 2nd Class Nicholas Brassard inspects rounds for the MK-38 25mm machine gun system.jpg|thumb|US Navy gunner inspects TP-T rounds]]\nThe current 25mm ammunition family consists of six combat and two training rounds:\n* [[Armour-piercing fin-stabilized discarding-sabot|APFSDS-T]]: armour-piercing fin stabilized discarding sabot with tracer, for use against armoured ground targets\n* [[Armour-piercing discarding sabot|APDS-T]]: armour-piercing discarding sabot with tracer, for use against armoured ground targets\n* FAPDS-T: frangible armour-piercing discarding sabot with tracer, for use against air, ground and urban targets\n* TPDS-T: target practice discarding sabot with tracer, a short range trainer for the above sub-calibre types\n* [[Semi-armor-piercing high-explosive incendiary|SAPHEI]]-T: semi-armour-piercing high explosive incendiary with tracer, for use against well protected targets\n* [[High-explosive incendiary|HEI]]-T: high explosive incendiary with tracer, for use against lightly protected targets\n* MP-T: multipurpose with tracer\n* TP-T: target practice with tracer, for training with the above full calibre types\n\n== Operators ==\n\n=== Current operators ===\n[[File:VBM Freccia visto frontalmente.JPG|thumb|Example of KBA gun installed on Italian 8x8 [[Freccia IFV|Freccia]] wheeled Infantry fighting vehicle in use with the Italian Army.]]\n*{{Flag|Bangladesh}}\n** [[Minerva-class corvette|Leader Class offshore patrol vessel]]\n** [[Sobuj Bangla-class patrol craft|''Sobuj Bangla''-class inshore patrol vessel]]\n* {{TUR}}\n** ASELSAN 25&nbsp;mm STOP Stabilized Naval Gun System<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/year-2015-news/july-2015-navy-naval-forces-defense-industry-technology-maritime-security-global-news/2935-aselsan-stop-25mm-remote-weapon-stations-for-pakistan-navy-fleet-tanker-project.html|title=Aselsan STOP 25mm Remote Weapon Stations for Pakistan Navy Fleet Tanker Project|work=Navy Recognition|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Egypt}}\n* {{ITA}}\n** [[FREMM]] multipurpose frigate\n** [[Italian aircraft carrier Cavour|CVH 550 ''Cavour'']] aircraft carrier\n** [[Freccia IFV|VBM Freccia infantry fighting vehicle]]\n** [[SIDAM 25]] self-propelled anti-aircraft gun\n** [[Horizon-class frigate]]\n* {{Flag|Japan}}\n** [[Type 87 ARV]]\n* {{Flag|Netherlands}}\n* {{Flag|Chile}}\n* {{Flag|Romania}}\n** [[MLI-84]] tracked infantry fighting vehicle\n* {{Flag|Bahrain}}\n* {{Flag|Turkmenistan}}\n*{{Flag|Malta}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Oerlikon-Contraves]]\n[[Category:Autocannon]]\n", "name_user": "Stefranci", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oerlikon_KBA"}
{"title_page": "Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale", "text_new": "[[File:Hugh Cecil Lowther, Vanity Fair, 1886-07-10.jpg|thumb|''Vanity Fair'' caricature, 10 July 1886]]\n[[File:Lowther coat of arms, stained glass window of St Michaels Church, Lowther Park (geograph 3205392).jpg|thumb|Arms of Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale, impaling Gordon, Marquess of Huntly]]\n'''Hugh Cecil Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KG|GCVO|DL}} (25 January 1857<ref name=\"Pocket On This Day\">{{cite book|title=Penguin Pocket On This Day|publisher=Penguin Reference Library|isbn=0-14-102715-0|year=2006}}</ref>\u201313 April 1944) was an [[English peer]] and sportsman.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:The_Imperial_German_Army_1890_-_1913_HU68454.jpg|thumb|left|Lord Lonsdale wearing the uniform of the [[Westmorland and Cumberland Yeomanry]] during the [[Imperial German Army]] manoeuvres of 1902]]\nThe second son of [[Henry Lowther, 3rd Earl of Lonsdale]], he succeeded his brother, [[St George Lowther, 4th Earl of Lonsdale]], in 1882.\n\n[[File:Hugh Cecil Lowther by Sir John Lavery circa 1920.jpg|thumb|Portrait (1930) by Sir [[John Lavery]] (1856-1941)]]\n\nBefore obtaining his inheritance, Hugh had in 1878 married Lady Grace Cecilie Gordon, third daughter of [[Charles Gordon, 10th Marquess of Huntly]]. Her family opposed the marriage as Hugh was then not wealthy and seemed irresponsible. This proved to be correct as the following year he invested in cattle in America; the venture collapsed and the Lowther family was forced to save him.\n\nThe couple then lived at [[Barleythorpe|Barleythorpe Hall]] near [[Oakham]]. Grace became pregnant but she had a  fall while hunting and lost the baby. After this she was unable to bear children and remained a partial invalid for the rest of her life.\n\n[[File:LowtherCastle.jpg|thumb|Lowther Castle - seat of the Earls of Lonsdale]]\n[[File:Shield of Arms of Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale, KG, GCVO, DL.png|thumb|Garter-encircled shield of arms of Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale, KG, as displayed on his Order of the Garter stall plate in St. George's Chapel.]]\nHe inherited enormous wealth, derived from [[Cumberland]] coalmines, and owned 75,000 acres of land. He had residences at [[Lowther Castle]], at [[Whitehaven Castle]], [[Barleythorpe]] and [[Carlton House Terrace]], London. He devoted his wealth to a life of ostentatious pleasure.\n\nAfter the scandal of an affair with the actress [[Violet Cameron]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/62581|title=Cameron, Violet (1862\u20131919) |last1= Foulkes |first1=Richard|last2= |first2= |date=2004 |website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> Lonsdale set out in 1888 to explore the [[Canadian Arctic|Arctic regions of Canada]] as far north as [[Melville Island (Northwest Territories and Nunavut)|Melville Island]], nearly dying before reaching [[Kodiak, Alaska]] in 1889<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1889/05/16/100960968.pdf New York Times, 16 May 1889]</ref> and returning to England. His collection of [[Inuit]] artefacts that he assembled during his explorations in Alaska and north-west Canada at this time is now in the [[British Museum]].<ref>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?people=116848&peoA=116848-3-9 British Museum Collection]</ref>\n\nLord Lonsdale was known as the Yellow Earl for his penchant for the colour. He was a founder and first president of [[the Automobile Association]] (AA) which adopted his livery. He was an avid sportsman and ''[[bon vivant]]'' and was known by some as \"England's greatest sporting gentleman\". He was a founding member and  first president of the [[National Sporting Club]] and he donated the original [[Lonsdale Belt]]s  in 1909 for the [[boxing]] championship trophy.  His name was later given to the [[Lonsdale (brand)|Lonsdale clothing brand]] of boxing garments and the [[Cigar#Styles|Lonsdale cigar size]].<ref>http://www.cigarchoiceguide.com/lonsdale.htm</ref>\n\nLonsdale was part of the [[Harry Bensley|famous wager]] with [[John Pierpont Morgan]] over whether a man could circumnavigate the globe and remain unidentified. He enjoyed [[foxhunting]], serving as Master of [[The Quorn]] from 1893 to 1898 and of the [[Cottesmore Hunt]] for long periods. He was also a keen [[football (soccer)|football]] fan, and was chairman of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal Football Club]] for a brief period in 1936 (having previously been a club director) and later became the club's honorary president.\n\nIn August 1895 the German Emperor [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Wilhelm II]] visited Lowther Castle for some [[grouse]] shooting. The kings of Italy and Portugal later came to stay, and the Kaiser a second time in 1902. The Kaiser conferred upon the Earl a knighthood of the first class of the [[Order of the Crown (Prussia)|Order of the Prussian Crown]].<ref>The New York Times 17 November 1902</ref>\n\nHe was Assistant [[Adjutant-General]] for the [[Imperial Yeomanry]] during the first part of the [[Second Boer War]], from 28 February 1900<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27169 |page=1351| date=27 February 1900}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27173| page=1715|date=13 March 1900}}</ref> until 1901. During the [[First World War]] his chief role was as a recruitment officer of both men and horses. He formed his own [[pals battalion]], the Lonsdales (11th Battalion, [[Border Regiment]]). He had helped to found [[The Blue Cross|Our Dumb Friends League]] (now Blue Cross) and was its chairman during the war.\n\nAfter the war, Hugh gave up hunting and became more involved with race horses. He became a senior steward of the [[Jockey Club]]. He had two major wins with his colt [[Royal Lancer]] in 1922, the [[St Leger]] and the [[Irish St Leger]]. He was also the first president of the [[International Horse Show]] at Olympia. Although he was a Peer, he was rarely seen in the [[House of Lords]].\n[[File:Lonsdale colours0001.jpg|thumb|left|Lord Lonsdale's racing colours by E & W Anstie Ltd cigarette card (1922)]]\n\nFrom 1929 Lonsdale was the joint editor of the ''Lonsdale Library of Sports, Games and Pastimes'', a book series published by Seeley, Service and Co.<ref>\"Books and Authors\", ''[[The Observer]]'', 3 February 1929, p. 8.</ref><ref>[https://www.publishinghistory.com/lonsdale-library-seeley-service.html The Lonsdale Library (Seeley, Service & Co.) - Book Series List], publishinghistory.com. Retrieved 24 March 2019.</ref>\n\nBecause of his extravagance he was forced to sell some of his inherited properties. In 1921 [[Whitehaven Castle]] was sold, and in 1926 [[Barleythorpe]]. The same year the west Cumberland coalmines closed. In 1935 he moved from [[Lowther Castle]] because he could no longer afford to live there and moved to much smaller accommodation. Grace died in 1941 and three years later, Hugh died at Stud House, Barleythorpe, aged 87.\n\nHis free-spending had largely wrecked the estate, and his heir, his brother [[Lancelot Lowther, 6th Earl of Lonsdale|Lancelot, the 6th Earl]] was forced to auction off the contents of Lowther Castle in 1947. This proved to be the largest [[English country house]] sale of the 20th Century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lowther.co.uk/castle/history2.php |title=Lowther Castle |accessdate=19 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071005155055/http://www.lowther.co.uk/castle/history2.php |archivedate=5 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLord Lonsdale was the subject of a [[Douglas Sutherland]] biography, ''The Yellow Earl: The life of Hugh Lowther'' (ISBN B0006BNPO6), published by  Cassell in 1965.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale}}\n*{{NPG name|name=Hugh Cecil Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale}}\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p1153.htm#i11524  The Peerage]\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | before=[[St George Lowther, 4th Earl of Lonsdale|St George Lowther]] | title=[[Earl of Lonsdale]] | after=[[Lancelot Lowther, 6th Earl of Lonsdale|Lancelot Lowther]] | years= 1882\u20131944}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Josslyn Pennington, 5th Baron Muncaster|The Lord Muncaster]] | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Cumberland]] | years=1917&ndash;1944 | after=Frescheville Hubert Ballantine-Dykes}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box |\n  title=[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] chairman |\n  before= [[Sir Samuel Hill-Wood, 1st Baronet|Sir Samuel Hill-Wood]] |\n  after= [[Bernard Forbes, 8th Earl of Granard|The Earl of Granard]] |\n  years=1936}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{British boxing}}\n{{boxing}}\n{{boxing History}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lonsdale, Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. directors and chairmen]]\n[[Category:British racehorse owners and breeders]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Rutland]]\n[[Category:English socialites]]\n[[Category:Founders of sporting institutions]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Legion of Frontiersmen members]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Cumberland]]\n[[Category:Lowther family|Hugh]]\n[[Category:Masters of foxhounds]]\n[[Category:People from Westmorland]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Hugh Cecil Lowther, Vanity Fair, 1886-07-10.jpg|thumb|''Vanity Fair'' caricature, 10 July 1886]]\n[[File:Lowther coat of arms, stained glass window of St Michaels Church, Lowther Park (geograph 3205392).jpg|thumb|Arms of Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale, impaling Gordon, Marquess of Huntly]]\n'''Hugh Cecil Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KG|GCVO|DL}} (25 January 1857<ref name=\"Pocket On This Day\">{{cite book|title=Penguin Pocket On This Day|publisher=Penguin Reference Library|isbn=0-14-102715-0|year=2006}}</ref>\u201313 April 1944) was an [[English peer]] and sportsman.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:The_Imperial_German_Army_1890_-_1913_HU68454.jpg|thumb|left|Lord Lonsdale wearing the uniform of the [[Westmorland and Cumberland Yeomanry]] during the [[Imperial German Army]] manoeuvres of 1902]]\nThe second son of [[Henry Lowther, 3rd Earl of Lonsdale]], he succeeded his brother, [[St George Lowther, 4th Earl of Lonsdale]], in 1882.\n\n[[File:Hugh Cecil Lowther by Sir John Lavery circa 1920.jpg|thumb|Portrait (1930) by Sir [[John Lavery]] (1856-1941)]]\n\nBefore obtaining his inheritance, Hugh had in 1878 married Lady Grace Cecilie Gordon, third daughter of [[Charles Gordon, 10th Marquess of Huntly]]. Her family opposed the marriage as Hugh was then not wealthy and seemed irresponsible. This proved to be correct as the following year he invested in cattle in America; the venture collapsed and the Lowther family was forced to save him.\n\nThe couple then lived at [[Barleythorpe|Barleythorpe Hall]] near [[Oakham]]. Grace became pregnant but she had a  fall while hunting and lost the baby. After this she was unable to bear children and remained a partial invalid for the rest of her life.\n\n[[File:LowtherCastle.jpg|thumb|Lowther Castle - seat of the Earls of Lonsdale]]\n[[File:Shield of Arms of Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale, KG, GCVO, DL.png|thumb|Garter-encircled shield of arms of Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale, KG, as displayed on his Order of the Garter stall plate in St. George's Chapel.]]\nHe inherited enormous wealth, derived from [[Cumberland]] coalmines, and owned 75,000 acres of land. He had residences at [[Lowther Castle]], at [[Whitehaven Castle]], [[Barleythorpe]] and [[Carlton House Terrace]], London. He devoted his wealth to a life of ostentatious pleasure.\n\nAfter the scandal of an affair with the actress [[Violet Cameron]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/62581|title=Cameron, Violet (1862\u20131919) |last1= Foulkes |first1=Richard|last2= |first2= |date=2004 |website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> Lonsdale set out in 1888 to explore the [[Canadian Arctic|Arctic regions of Canada]] as far north as [[Melville Island (Northwest Territories and Nunavut)|Melville Island]], nearly dying before reaching [[Kodiak, Alaska]] in 1889<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1889/05/16/100960968.pdf New York Times, 16 May 1889]</ref> and returning to England. His collection of [[Inuit]] artefacts that he assembled during his explorations in Alaska and north-west Canada at this time is now in the [[British Museum]].<ref>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?people=116848&peoA=116848-3-9 British Museum Collection]</ref>\n\nLord Lonsdale was known as the Yellow Earl for his penchant for the colour. He was a founder and first president of [[the Automobile Association]] (AA) which adopted his livery. He was an avid sportsman and ''[[bon vivant]]'' and was known by some as \"England's greatest sporting gentleman\". He was a founding member and  first president of the [[National Sporting Club]] and he donated the original [[Lonsdale Belt]]s  in 1909 for the [[boxing]] championship trophy.  His name was later given to the [[Lonsdale (brand)|Lonsdale clothing brand]] of boxing garments and the [[Cigar#Styles|Lonsdale cigar size]].<ref>http://www.cigarchoiceguide.com/lonsdale.htm</ref>\n\nLonsdale was part of the [[Harry Bensley|famous wager]] with [[John Pierpont Morgan]] over whether a man could circumnavigate the globe and remain unidentified. He enjoyed [[foxhunting]], serving as Master of [[The Quorn]] from 1893 to 1898 and of the [[Cottesmore Hunt]] for long periods. He was also a keen [[football (soccer)|football]] fan, and was chairman of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal Football Club]] for a brief period in 1936 (having previously been a club director) and later became the club's honorary president.\n\nIn August 1895 the German Emperor [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Wilhelm II]] visited Lowther Castle for some [[grouse]] shooting. The kings of Italy and Portugal later came to stay, and the Kaiser a second time in 1902. The Kaiser conferred upon the Earl a knighthood of the first class of the [[Order of the Crown (Prussia)|Order of the Prussian Crown]].<ref>The New York Times 17 November 1902</ref>\n\nHe was Assistant [[Adjutant-General]] for the [[Imperial Yeomanry]] during the first part of the [[Second Boer War]], from 28 February 1900<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27169 |page=1351| date=27 February 1900}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27173| page=1715|date=13 March 1900}}</ref> until 1901. During the ][[First World War]] his chief role was as a recruitment officer of both men and horses. He formed his own [[pals battalion]], the Lonsdales (11th Battalion, [[Border Regiment]]). He had helped to found [[The Blue Cross|Our Dumb Friends League]] (now Blue Cross) and was its chairman during the war.\n\nAfter the war, Hugh gave up hunting and became more involved with race horses. He became a senior steward of the [[Jockey Club]]. He had two major wins with his colt [[Royal Lancer]] in 1922, the [[St Leger]] and the [[Irish St Leger]]. He was also the first president of the [[International Horse Show]] at Olympia. Although he was a Peer, he was rarely seen in the [[House of Lords]].\n[[File:Lonsdale colours0001.jpg|thumb|left|Lord Lonsdale's racing colours by E & W Anstie Ltd cigarette card (1922)]]\n\nFrom 1929 Lonsdale was the joint editor of the ''Lonsdale Library of Sports, Games and Pastimes'', a book series published by Seeley, Service and Co.<ref>\"Books and Authors\", ''[[The Observer]]'', 3 February 1929, p. 8.</ref><ref>[https://www.publishinghistory.com/lonsdale-library-seeley-service.html The Lonsdale Library (Seeley, Service & Co.) - Book Series List], publishinghistory.com. Retrieved 24 March 2019.</ref>\n\nBecause of his extravagance he was forced to sell some of his inherited properties. In 1921 [[Whitehaven Castle]] was sold, and in 1926 [[Barleythorpe]]. The same year the west Cumberland coalmines closed. In 1935 he moved from [[Lowther Castle]] because he could no longer afford to live there and moved to much smaller accommodation. Grace died in 1941 and three years later, Hugh died at Stud House, Barleythorpe, aged 87.\n\nHis free-spending had largely wrecked the estate, and his heir, his brother [[Lancelot Lowther, 6th Earl of Lonsdale|Lancelot, the 6th Earl]] was forced to auction off the contents of Lowther Castle in 1947. This proved to be the largest [[English country house]] sale of the 20th Century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lowther.co.uk/castle/history2.php |title=Lowther Castle |accessdate=19 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071005155055/http://www.lowther.co.uk/castle/history2.php |archivedate=5 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLord Lonsdale was the subject of a [[Douglas Sutherland]] biography, ''The Yellow Earl: The life of Hugh Lowther'' (ISBN B0006BNPO6), published by  Cassell in 1965.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale}}\n*{{NPG name|name=Hugh Cecil Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale}}\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p1153.htm#i11524  The Peerage]\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | before=[[St George Lowther, 4th Earl of Lonsdale|St George Lowther]] | title=[[Earl of Lonsdale]] | after=[[Lancelot Lowther, 6th Earl of Lonsdale|Lancelot Lowther]] | years= 1882\u20131944}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Josslyn Pennington, 5th Baron Muncaster|The Lord Muncaster]] | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Cumberland]] | years=1917&ndash;1944 | after=Frescheville Hubert Ballantine-Dykes}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box |\n  title=[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] chairman |\n 