{"title_page": "Amit Bhatia", "text_new": "{{short description|British-Indian businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Amit bhatia portrait swordfish hope construction london office.jpg|thumbnail|right|Amit Bhatia]] -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Amit Bhatia\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|09|04|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[London, United Kingdom]]\n|alma_mater = [[Cornell University]]\n|occupation = Owner, Swordfish Investments; ex-Chairman, [[Hope Construction Materials]]; Chairman, [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], Non Exec Chairman [https://www.breedongroup.com/ Breedon Group]\n|spouse(s) = Vanisha Mittal Bhatia\n|awards = Asian Business Young Entrepreneur of the Year}}\n\n'''Amit Bhatia''' (born 4 September 1979) is a [[British Indian|British-Indian]] businessman. He is the founding partner of Swordfish Investments and chairman of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] football club.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nAmit Bhatia was born in London, United Kingdom. He was educated in [[Delhi]] at [[St. Columba's School, Delhi|Columba's School]]  until 1995, followed by [[Dulwich College]] in London, United Kingdom, in 1996, and at [[The British School, New Delhi|British School]] in Delhi in 1997. Bhatia attended [[Cornell University]]  where he studied Economics. He has since remained involved in alumni matters, now serving on Cornell's External Advisory Council for Internalization. He has lectured at the University's Johnson School for MBA students.\n\nIn 2004 Bhatia married Vanisha Mittal, the daughter of steel tycoon and Chairman and CEO of [[ArcelorMittal]], [[Lakshmi Mittal]], in a ceremony said to have cost as much as \u00a360 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Most Outrageous Billionaire Weddings|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/mlf45hgej/vanisha-mittal-and-amit-bhatia/ | work=Forbes | first=Clare|last=O'Connor}}</ref> They have three children.\n\n==Career==\nBhatia began his career working in mergers and acquisitions at [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Merrill Lynch]] in New York before moving to [[Credit Suisse First Boston]] in London. He then incubated [[Swordfish Investments]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Swordfish Investments|url=https://www.swordfishinvestments.com/}}</ref> \n, a Mayfair-based private equity/venture fund, and Swordfish Capital Management, an investment management company. Investments included education, media, telecoms, financial services, technology, consumer goods and real estate. \n\n\nBhatia was the Chairman of [[Hope Construction Materials]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Hope Construction Materials|url=http://www.londonlovesbusiness.com/entrepreneurs/famous-entrepreneurs/amit-bhatia-is-lakshmi-mittals-son-in-law-and-qpr-co-owner-is-there-more-to-him/5599.article/}}</ref> the UK's largest independent cement aggregates and concrete company. The company was formed in January 2013 after the divestment of 200 sites by two of the UK's biggest building materials companies, [[Tarmac Group]] and [[Lafarge (company)|Lafarge]]. Hope's assets include the largest cement works in the UK at [[Hope Valley in Derbyshire]], 172 ready-mix plants, 4 rail heads, 5 major quarries, 7 national offices, a fleet of over 400 tanker and mixer vehicles and over 1000 employees. The company was the UK's first construction firm to join the World Economic Forum's Global Growth Companies (GGC) community and one of just two European construction firms to meet membership criteria.\n\nIn August 2016, Bhatia sold Hope to Breedon Aggregates, making the newly formed [[Breedon Group]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Breedon Groups|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/breedon-to-acquire-hope-for-336m/}}</ref>  the UK's largest independent construction materials group. Bhatia joined the board as a non-executive director following its acquisition and is a substantial shareholder of the company. In April 2018, Bhatia was promoted to become its Deputy Chairman <ref>{{cite news|title=Breedon Appoints Deputy Chairman|url=https://www.worldcement.com/europe-cis/30042018/breedon-appoints-amit-bhatia-deputy-chairman/}}</ref> and in May 2019 Bhatia was appointed as Chairman of the Board. <ref>{{cite news|title=Breedon Appoints Chairman of the Board|url=https://www.pbctoday.co.uk/news/hr-skills-news/amit-bhatia-breedon/57678/\n}}</ref>\n\nHis other business interests encompass real estate and technology. Bhatia is a partner of Summix, a strategic land fund with a nationwide portfolio of assets that has delivered thousands of homes across the UK and Ireland since 2006.  In 2017, he helped launch Summix Capital as a vehicle to help deliver larger and more complex projects.<ref>{{cite news|title=Summix|url=https://summix.com/}}</ref>  \n\nHe is also a partner of Initial Capital, an investor in seed and early-stage technology companies with a focus on games and consumer services.  Initial Capital is based out of London and Silicon Valley, and has played a key role in growing its portfolio companies. <ref>{{cite news|title=Initial Capital|url=http://www.initialcapital.com//}}</ref>  \n\nBhatia serves on the Advisory Board of Metro Bank, is a William Pitt Group group member at Chatham House and a Gold Leaf member of the Aspen Institute. He was awarded Young Entrepreneur of the Year by Theresa May in 2013, Outstanding Young Executive of the Year and Young Director of the Year in 2014.\n\n==Sports==\nIn 2007 Bhatia bought a stake in Queens Park Rangers FC. He has served as the Vice-Chairman from 2007 for almost a decade. \n\nOn 15 August 2018, Bhatia was appointed chairman of the club after co-chairmen Tony Fernandes and Ruben Gnanalingam vacated their positions[7]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhatia, Amit}}\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. directors and chairmen]]\n[[Category:Samuel Curtis Johnson Graduate School of Management alumni]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:St. Columba's School, Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dulwich College]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British-Indian businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Amit bhatia portrait swordfish hope construction london office.jpg|thumbnail|right|Amit Bhatia]] -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Amit Bhatia\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|09|04|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[London, United Kingdom]]\n|alma_mater = [[Cornell University]]\n|occupation = Owner, Swordfish Investments; ex-Chairman, [[Hope Construction Materials]]; Chairman, [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], Non Exec Chairman [https://www.breedongroup.com/ Breedon Group]\n|spouse(s) = Vanisha Mittal Bhatia\n|awards = Asian Business Young Entrepreneur of the Year}}\n\n'''Amit Bhatia''' (born 4 September 1979) is a [[British Indian|British-Indian]] businessman. He is the founding partner of Swordfish Investments and chairman of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] football club.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nAmit Bhatia was born in London, United Kingdom to Arun Bhatia and wife Renu. He was educated in [[Delhi]] at [[St. Columba's School, Delhi|Columba's School]] until 1995, followed by [[Dulwich College]] in London, United Kingdom, in 1996, and at the [[The British School, New Delhi|British School]] in Delhi in 1997. Bhatia is an alumnus of [[Cornell University]] where he studied Economics. He has since remained involved in alumni matters, now serving on Cornell's External Advisory Council for Internalization. He has lectured at the University's Johnson School for MBA students.\n\nIn 2004 Bhatia married Vanisha Mittal, the daughter of steel tycoon and Chairman and CEO of [[ArcelorMittal]], [[Lakshmi Mittal]], in a ceremony said to have cost as much as \u00a360 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Most Outrageous Billionaire Weddings|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/mlf45hgej/vanisha-mittal-and-amit-bhatia/ | work=Forbes | first=Clare|last=O'Connor}}</ref> They have three children.\n\n==Career==\nBhatia began his career working in mergers and acquisitions at [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Merrill Lynch]] in New York before moving to [[Credit Suisse First Boston]] in London. He then incubated [[Swordfish Investments]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Swordfish Investments|url=https://www.swordfishinvestments.com/}}</ref> \n, a Mayfair-based private equity/venture fund, and Swordfish Capital Management, an investment management company. Investments included education, media, telecoms, financial services, technology, consumer goods and real estate. \n\n\nBhatia was the Chairman of [[Hope Construction Materials]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Hope Construction Materials|url=http://www.londonlovesbusiness.com/entrepreneurs/famous-entrepreneurs/amit-bhatia-is-lakshmi-mittals-son-in-law-and-qpr-co-owner-is-there-more-to-him/5599.article/}}</ref> the UK's largest independent cement aggregates and concrete company. The company was formed in January 2013 after the divestment of 200 sites by two of the UK's biggest building materials companies, [[Tarmac Group]] and [[Lafarge (company)|Lafarge]]. Hope's assets include the largest cement works in the UK at [[Hope Valley in Derbyshire]], 172 ready-mix plants, 4 rail heads, 5 major quarries, 7 national offices, a fleet of over 400 tanker and mixer vehicles and over 1000 employees. The company was the UK's first construction firm to join the World Economic Forum's Global Growth Companies (GGC) community and one of just two European construction firms to meet membership criteria.\n\nIn August 2016, Bhatia sold Hope to Breedon Aggregates, making the newly formed [[Breedon Group]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Breedon Groups|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/breedon-to-acquire-hope-for-336m/}}</ref>  the UK's largest independent construction materials group. Bhatia joined the board as a non-executive director following its acquisition and is a substantial shareholder of the company. In April 2018, Bhatia was promoted to become its Deputy Chairman <ref>{{cite news|title=Breedon Appoints Deputy Chairman|url=https://www.worldcement.com/europe-cis/30042018/breedon-appoints-amit-bhatia-deputy-chairman/}}</ref> and in May 2019 Bhatia was appointed as Chairman of the Board. <ref>{{cite news|title=Breedon Appoints Chairman of the Board|url=https://www.pbctoday.co.uk/news/hr-skills-news/amit-bhatia-breedon/57678/\n}}</ref>\n\nHis other business interests encompass real estate and technology. Bhatia is a partner of Summix, a strategic land fund with a nationwide portfolio of assets that has delivered thousands of homes across the UK and Ireland since 2006.  In 2017, he helped launch Summix Capital as a vehicle to help deliver larger and more complex projects.<ref>{{cite news|title=Summix|url=https://summix.com/}}</ref>  \n\nHe is also a partner of Initial Capital, an investor in seed and early-stage technology companies with a focus on games and consumer services.  Initial Capital is based out of London and Silicon Valley, and has played a key role in growing its portfolio companies. <ref>{{cite news|title=Initial Capital|url=http://www.initialcapital.com//}}</ref>  \n\nBhatia serves on the Advisory Board of Metro Bank, is a William Pitt Group group member at Chatham House and a Gold Leaf member of the Aspen Institute. He was awarded Young Entrepreneur of the Year by Theresa May in 2013, Outstanding Young Executive of the Year and Young Director of the Year in 2014.\n\n==Sports==\nIn 2007 Bhatia bought a stake in [[Queens Park Rangers FC]]. He has served as their Vice-Chairman since then with the exception of a brief time in 2011,<ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Fernandes is chasing the impossible dream |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/queens-park-rangers/9495929/QPR-chairman-Tony-Fernandes-is-chasing-the-impossible-dream.html/| work=The Telegraph |location=London| first=Thom| last=Gibbs| date=23 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222082438/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/queens-park-rangers/9495929/QPR-chairman-Tony-Fernandes-is-chasing-the-impossible-dream.html |archivedate=22 February 2014 }}</ref> when he resigned from QPR's board in frustration after his bid to buy the whole club was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web|title=QPR vice-chairman Amit Bhatia quits over board fall-out|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/13550798/| publisher=BBC Sport| date=25 May 2011| first=Dan| last=Roan}}</ref> He returned to the board a few months later.\n\nOn 15 August 2018, Bhatia was appointed chairman of the club after co-chairmen [[Tony Fernandes]] and [[Ruben Gnanalingam]] vacated their positions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qpr.co.uk/news/club-news/amit-bhatia-appointed-new-chairman-of-qpr/|title=Amit Bhatia appointed new chairman of QPR|publisher=Queens Park Rangers F.C.|first=David|last=Scriven|date=15 August 2018|language=EN|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhatia, Amit}}\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. directors and chairmen]]\n[[Category:Samuel Curtis Johnson Graduate School of Management alumni]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:St. Columba's School, Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dulwich College]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c6:6a98:2900:9c6a:fc33:db0:1778", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSports)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amit_Bhatia"}
{"title_page": "Kane Williamson", "text_new": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|New Zealand cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Kane Williamson\n| fullname = Kane Stuart Williamson\n| image = Kane Williamson in 2019.jpg\n| caption = Williamson, captaining New Zealand, in 2019\n| nickname = <!-- please cite nicknames if they're not on CricInfo -->\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|8|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Tauranga]], New Zealand\n| heightft = 5\n| heightinch = 8\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[off-break]]\n| role = [[Batting order (cricket)|Batsman]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2010-present\n| country = New Zealand\n| testdebutdate = 4 November\n| testdebutyear = 2010\n| testdebutagainst = India\n| testcap = 248\n| lasttestdate = 29 February\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = India\n| odidebutdate = 10 August\n| odidebutyear = 2010\n| odidebutagainst = India\n| odicap = 161\n| lastodidate = 13 March\n| lastodiyear = 2020\n| lastodiagainst = Australia\n| T20Idebutdate = 16 October\n| T20Idebutyear = 2011\n| T20Idebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| T20Icap = 49\n| lastT20Idate = 29 January\n| lastT20Iyear = 2020\n| lastT20Iagainst = India\n| club1 = [[Northern Districts cricket team|Northern Districts]]\n| year1 = {{nowrap|2007/08\u2013present}}\n| club2 = [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]]\n| year2 = 2011\u20132012\n| club3 = [[Yorkshire Cricket Club|Yorkshire]]\n| year3 = 2013\u20132018\n| club4 = [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]]\n| year4 = 2015\u2013present\n| club6 = [[Barbados Tridents]]\n| year6 = 2017\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 80\n| runs1 = 6,476\n| bat avg1 = 50.99\n| 100s/50s1 = 21/32\n| top score1 = 242[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries1 = 2,103\n| wickets1 = 29\n| bowl avg1 = 40.62\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 4/44\n| catches/stumpings1 = 71/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 151\n| runs2 = 6,173\n| bat avg2 = 47.48\n| 100s/50s2 = 13/39\n| top score2 = 148\n| deliveries2 = 1,467\n| wickets2 = 37\n| bowl avg2 = 35.40\n| fivefor2 = 0\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 4/22\n| catches/stumpings2 = 60/\u2013\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n| matches3 = 60\n| runs3 = 1,665\n| bat avg3 = 32.64\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/11\n| top score3 = 95\n| deliveries3 = 118\n| wickets3 = 6\n| bowl avg3 = 27.33\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 2/16\n| catches/stumpings3 = 27/\u2013\n| column4 = [[First class cricket|FC]]\n| matches4 = 147\n| runs4 = 11,279\n| bat avg4 = 48.82\n| 100s/50s4 = 31/59\n| top score4 = 284[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries4 = 6,576\n| wickets4 = 85\n| bowl avg4 = 43.43\n| fivefor4 = 1\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 5/75\n| catches/stumpings4 = 135/\u2013\n| date = 13 March \n| year = 2020\n| source = http://espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/277906.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Kane Stuart Williamson''' (born 8 August 1990) is a New Zealand international [[cricket]]er who is currently the [[Captain (cricket)|captain]] of the [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand national team]] in all formats. He's widely regarded as one of the best batsmen of his generation. He is a right-handed batsman and an occasional [[off spin]] bowler.  Williamson made his [[first-class cricket]] debut in December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/159/159052/First-Class_Matches.html|title=List of First Class Matches Played by Kane Williamson|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref> He made his U-19 debut against the touring [[India Under-19 cricket team|Indian U-19 team]] the same year and was named captain of the [[New Zealand Under-19 cricket team|New Zealand U-19 team]] for the [[2008 U-19 Cricket World Cup]]. He made his international debut in 2010. Williamson has represented New Zealand at the [[2011 ICC Cricket World Cup|2011]], [[2015 ICC Cricket World Cup|2015]] and [[2019 ICC Cricket World Cup|2019]] editions of the [[Cricket World Cup]] and [[2012 ICC World Twenty20|2012]], [[2014 ICC World Twenty20|2014]] and [[2016 ICC World Twenty20|2016]] editions of the [[ICC World Twenty20]]. He made his full-time captaincy debut for [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] in the 2016 ICC World Twenty20 in [[India]]. He captained [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand national team]] in [[2019 Cricket World Cup]] and led the team to the finals. He was then awarded the [[Cricket World Cup awards#Awards summary |Player of the Tournament]] award. \n\nAt various times [[Ian Chappell]] and [[Martin Crowe]] have ranked Williamson among the top four or five Test cricket batsmen, along with [[Joe Root]], [[Steve Smith (cricketer)|Steve Smith]], [[Virat Kohli]] and [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Test cricket's young Fab Four|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/774705.html|publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Virat Kohli, Joe Root, Steven Smith, Kane Williamson \u2018Fab Four\u2019 of Tests: Martin Crowe|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/virat-kohli-joe-root-steven-smith-kane-williamson-fab-four-of-tests-martin-crowe/|publisher=The Indian Express |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/20727319/big-four-ought-five-warner-there|title=Big four? What about Warner?|work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKane Williamson was born on 8 August 1990 in [[Tauranga]], New Zealand. He played senior representative cricket at the age of 14 and first-class cricket at 16. Williamson attended [[Tauranga Boys' College]] from 2004\u20132008, where he was head boy in his final year and was coached by Pacey Depina. Depina described Williamson as having \"a thirst to be phenomenal \u2013 but not at anyone else's expense.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cumming|first1=Geoff|title=More than able Kane|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11413192|website=NZ Herald|publisher=NZ Herald|accessdate=2015-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Kane Williamson: 19 facts about the Kiwi superstar|url = http://www.criclife.com/lists/chronicles/kane-williamson-19-facts-about-the-kiwi-superstar-43820|website = CricLife|date = 2015-08-08|accessdate = 2015-12-22}}</ref> He reportedly scored 40 centuries before he left school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecricketmonthly.com/story/879501/kane-is-able|title=Kane is able|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Domestic career ==\n=== Northern Districts ===\nWilliamson made his debut for Northern Districts in 2007 at the age of 17, who he has remained with for the duration of his New Zealand domestic career.\n\n=== English county cricket ===\nWilliamson signed for [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]] to play in the [[2011 English cricket season|2011 English county season]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Williamson joins Gloucestershire|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/505808.html|work=ESPNCricinfo|date=12 March 2011|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> On 14 August 2013, he signed for [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]] for the rest of the season and subsequently signed to return for the [[2014 English cricket season|2014 season]], when his side won the County Championship.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Yorkshire sign New Zealand batsman Kane Williamson |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/23695847 |work=BBC Sport|date=14 August 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Yorkshire: Kane Williamson to be overseas player for 2014 season |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/24224196 |work=BBC Sport|date=24 September 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> He signed to return the latter part of the [[2015 English cricket season|2015 season]], but when incumbent overseas player [[Aaron Finch]] was not selected for the Australia ODI squad, Yorkshire ultimately chose to extend Finch's deal in place of Williamson.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Kane Williamson: Yorkshire re-sign New Zealand batsman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/31518727 |work=BBC Sport|date=18 February 2015 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Williamson not required after Finch returns |url=http://www.ecb.co.uk/news/articles/williamson-not-required-after-finch-returns |work=ECB |date=21 August 2015 |accessdate=27 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203124627/http://www.ecb.co.uk/news/articles/williamson-not-required-after-finch-returns |archive-date=3 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He subsequently signed a deal for part of the [[2016 English cricket season|2016 season]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Kane Williamson: Yorkshire re-sign New Zealand batsman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/35417777 |work=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2016 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Indian Premier League (IPL) ===\nOn 6 February 2015, [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]] of the IPL signed Williamson for US$96,500. He played for Sunrisers Hyderabad in the [[2016 Indian Premier League|2016 season]] where they won the title. For the [[2017 Indian Premier League]] he was retained by the side. In the [[List of 2018 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2018 IPL Auction]], he was retained by the Sunrisers Hyderabad for US$460,500. On 29 March 2018, he was announced captain of Sunrisers Hyderabad replacing [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/SunRisers/status/979263226746753024|title=SunRisers Hyderabad on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/101315/kane-williamson-appointed-sunrisers-hyderabad-cricket-team-captain-for-ipl-2018|title=Kane Williamson appointed SRH captain for IPL 2018 He also won the Orange cap (leading run scorer) on the same edition.In the 2019 version of Vivo IPL he transferred his captaincy duties to Bhuvneshwar Kumar because of his shoulder injury not allowing him to play some games.|work=Cricbuzz|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en}}</ref> Under Williamson's captaincy Sunrisers Hyderabad finished runners-up after [[Chennai Super Kings]] defeated them in the [[2018 Indian Premier League Final|final]] by 8 wickets, he also won the [[Orange Cap]] for scoring the most runs (735) in the [[2018 Indian Premier League|2018 IPL season]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/cricketnext/news/ipl-2018-kane-williamson-takes-orange-cap-becomes-third-highest-scorer-in-single-season-1761105.html|title=IPL 2018: Kane Williamson Takes Orange Cap, Becomes Third Highest-scorer in Single Season|date=2018-05-28|work=News18|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> He was named in the IPL XI of the tournament by Cricbuzz.<ref>https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/102276/cb-xi-team-of-ipl-2018</ref>\n\n===Other franchise cricket===\nIn June 2019, he was selected to play for the Edmonton Royals franchise team in the [[2019 Global T20 Canada]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadacricket.com/?p=12755 |title=Global T20 draft streamed live |work=Canada Cricket Online |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n=== Early days ===\nWilliamson was 17, when he led the New Zealand Under-19 side in the World Cup in Malaysia in 2008. New Zealand reached the semi-final, where they lost to the eventual champions India. On 24 March 2010, Williamson was named in the New Zealand Test squad for the second Test against Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/nzvaus2010/content/current/story/453236.html|title=Kane Williamson named in New Zealand Test squad|last=Coverdale|first=Brydon|date=24 March 2010|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=24 March 2010}}</ref> but ultimately he did not play in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/nzvaus2010/engine/current/match/423790.html|title=Scorecard \u2013 2nd Test: New Zealand v Australia at Hamilton, 27\u201331&nbsp;March 2010|publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate=6 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson made his [[One-Day International]] debut against [[India national cricket team|India]] on 10 August 2010. He was dismissed for a 9th ball [[Duck (cricket)|duck]]. In his second match, he was bowled by [[Angelo Mathews]] for a second ball duck. He scored his maiden ODI [[Century (cricket)|century]] against [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]] on 14 October 2010 in [[Dhaka]] and hence became the youngest centurion in New Zealand's cricket history. Due to his performance on the [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2010\u201311|Bangladesh tour]] where New Zealand suffered a 4\u20130 whitewash, Williamson was selected in the New Zealand Test squad for the [[New Zealand cricket team in India in 2010\u201311|tour of India]] that followed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india-v-new-zealand-2010/content/current/story/483282.html|title=Williamson, Bennett in Test squad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson made his [[Test cricket]] debut against [[India national cricket team|India]] at [[Ahmedabad]] on 4 November 2010. In his first innings he scored 131 runs off 299 balls and became the eighth [[List of Test cricket records for New Zealand#Centuries|New Zealand player to score a century on Test debut]].<ref name=\"TestDebut\">{{cite web|title=ESPNcricinfo : New Zealand tour of India (Nov 2010), 1st Test: India v New Zealand at Ahmedabad, Nov&nbsp;4\u20138, 2010|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india-v-new-zealand-2010/engine/current/match/464531.html|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=6 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/485892.html|title=Williamson and Vettori guide New Zealand past 400|author=Ravindran, Siddarth|date=7 November 2010|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Rising through the ranks ===\nHe was selected in the 2nd XI of the 2014 ICC World T20 Cup by ESPNCricinfo.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/world-t20/content/story/735589.html</ref> He was also named in the Test XI of the year by Cricbuzz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/67765/2014-review-test-team-of-the-year|title=2014 review: Test team of the year\n|work=Cricbuzz |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson scored test match score of 161 against West Indies in June 2014. It was his second test century of the series and helped secure a rare away test series victory for his side. Williamson finished as the leading overall run scorer in the series with 413 runs, and was denied a double century only by rain, which forced skipper [[Brendon McCullum]] to declare in the interest of obtaining a result in the match. He was also reported for a suspect bowling action in April 2014, but was cleared in December 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AihgstaAlp0|title=See Kane Williamson's new bowling action|date=9 December 2014|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sachithra Senanayake & Kane Williamson cleared to bowl again |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/30394969 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 December 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014 }}</ref> His [[illegal bowling action]] started after he left high school in order to get a faster release and turn on the ball.  His new action essentially reverts him to his action in high school, with a more side-on approach and less wrist and elbow deviation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ho3TQNrdsb8|title=Kane Williamson First Test Over With New Bowling Action|date=28 December 2014|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> He was also named as captain ahead of the ODI and Twenty20 series against Pakistan as Brendon McCullum was rested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/67160/kane-williamson-named-as-captain-for-pakistan-series-brendon-mccullum-rested|title=Kane Williamson named as captain for Pakistan series; Brendon McCullum rested|work=Cricbuzz|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kane Williamson (9773667991).jpg|thumb|234x234px|Williamson batting against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] in 2013]]\nWilliamson is currently third on the list (behind Corey Anderson and Jesse Ryder) for the highest ever strike-rated century by a New Zealander in a [[One-Day International]]. He achieved the feat during his 100[[not out|*]] off 69 balls [[New Zealand cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2011\u201312#3rd ODI|against Zimbabwe]] at [[Bulawayo]].<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;orderby=batting_strike_rate;runsmin1=100;runsval1=runs;size=150;team=5;template=results;t Statistics / Statsguru / One-Day Internationals / Batting records] ESPNcricinfo Statsguru. Retrieved 29 December 2011</ref> On 19 September 2014 he scored his first T20 hundred scoring 101[[not out|*]] in 49 balls to guide [[Northern Districts]] for a comfortable win against [[Cape Cobras]] in [[Champions League Twenty20]] 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/champions-league-twenty20-2014/content/story/782333.html|title=Kane Williamson ton crushes Cobras \u2013  Cricket  \u2013 ESPNcricinfo|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>  He has also established one of the most potent no. 3-no. 4 [[Batting order (cricket)#Top order|top-order]] partnership with [[Ross Taylor]], with himself being the most prolific no. 3 batsman for the national side since former captain [[Stephen Fleming]].Apart from Fleming (in 2006), Williamson (in 2015) became the most recent no. 3 New Zealand batsmen to score a double century in Test cricket. However, Williamson and Taylor were also involved in 12 run outs across all forms of international cricket as of 26 January 2015 when they are both on the crease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/sport/black-caps-await-final-one-dayer-before-world-cup-2015012620|title=Black Caps await final one dayer before World Cup \u2013 Sport \u2013 3 News|author=David Di Somma|work=3news.co.nz|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> As a fielder, his position is predominantly at gully,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FeD7CQrtV8U|title=Kane Williamson Incredible Gully Catch vs. Sri Lanka (Wellington 2015)|date=6 January 2015|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> but can move to point with spin bowlers, or cover point or long off with fast bowlers.\n\nIn 2015, he started with 69 and 242[[not out|*]] against Sri Lanka, with two catches in the field in a man-of-the-match performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-sri-lanka-2014-15/content/story/817747.html|title=Williamson could be our greatest ever batter \u2013 McCullum|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>  On 3 February 2015, he helped New Zealand score the 99th ODI century in the team's history against Pakistan; Ross Taylor scored the 100th in the same match. He also scored over 700 runs before the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]] in just the first two months of the calendar year. On 17 June 2015 he became the fifth-fastest batsmen and fastest New Zealander to score 3,000 runs, getting them in just 78 innings. On 15 November 2015 Williamson and Taylor became the first pair of away batsmen to each score 2nd innings centuries at [[List of international cricket centuries at the WACA Ground|WACA Ground]] in [[Perth]].\n\nIn December 2015, during the [[Sri Lankan cricket team in New Zealand in 2015\u201316|second Test against Sri Lanka]], Williamson broke the record for the most Test runs scored in a calendar year by a New Zealander, with 1172 runs.<ref name=\"2ndTest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-sri-lanka-2015-16/content/story/953745.html |title=Williamson's record ton and NZ's longest unbeaten streak at home |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 December 2015| accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> He also ended 2015 with 2692 runs, the highest score across all forms of international cricket for the year, and third highest totals in a single year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=555268464622721&set=o.203262656377121&type=3&theater|title=William Q\u00fcensell|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor his performances in 2015, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC, Cricbuzz and ESPNCricinfo.<ref>https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/182259</ref><ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2015/content/story/956299.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/76936/cricbuzz-team-of-the-year-2015|title=Cricbuzz Team of the Year 2015\n|work=Cricbuzz |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> He was also named in the ODI XI of the year 2015 by Cricinfo.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2015/content/story/956299.html</ref>\n\nHe was awarded the T20 Player of the Year by NZC for the 2014-15 season.<ref>http://nzcricketmuseum.co.nz/new-zealand-cricket-awards/</ref>\n\n=== Captaincy ===\nIn March 2016, Williamson assumed the position of captain of New Zealand across all forms of cricket after the retirement of Brendon McCullum, beginning with the World T20I cup in India. He was named as captain of the 'Team of the Tournament' by Cricinfo and Cricbuzz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/995203.html|title=ESPNcricinfo's team of the 2016 World T20|website=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/79133/cricbuzz-team-of-the-icc-world-t20-2016|title=Cricbuzz Team of the ICC World T20, 2016|website=Cricbuzz}}</ref> He also picked up NZ player of the year, Test player of the year and the Redpath Cup for top batsman in first class cricket for the second year in a row.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cricket.com.au/news/brendon-mccullum-wins-new-zealand-sir-richard-hadlee-medal-after-world-cup/2015-04-02\n| title = McCullum named cricketer of year\n| website = cricket.com.au\n| access-date = 25 February 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.newshub.co.nz/sport/williamson-cleans-up-at-nz-cricket-awards-2016022521#axzz40q3ulDBA\n| title = Williamson cleans up at NZ Cricket Awards\n| website = Newshub.co.nz\n| access-date = 25 February 2016\n}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, during the [[New Zealand cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2016|Test series against Zimbabwe]], Williamson became the thirteenth batsman to score a century against all the other Test playing nations. He completed this in the fewest innings, the quickest time from his Test debut and became the youngest player to achieve this feat.<ref name=\"WilliamsonZim\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-new-zealand-2016/content/story/1043641.html |title=Williamson racks up the records |accessdate=7 August 2016 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> In the complete list of such batsmen, he has achieved this feat with the smallest number of total centuries.\n\nFor his performances in 2016, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC.<ref>https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/the-full-list-of-icc-awards-2016-winners/story-HwiwPQa1CPLmYV6y7hx6vM.html></ref>\n\nFor his performances in the 2015-16 and 2016-17 seasons, he won the Sir Richard Hadlee Medal.<ref>http://nzcricketmuseum.co.nz/new-zealand-cricket-awards/</ref> He also was awarded the T20 Player of the Year by NZC for the 2016-17 season.<ref>http://nzcricketmuseum.co.nz/new-zealand-cricket-awards/</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2017, Williamson joined [[Ross Taylor]] as joint second highest (first amongst active players) on NZ's Test century list, both one behind [[Martin Crowe]]. Williamson also took the fewest matches to score at least 16 centuries at 26 years of age ([[Alastair Cook|Cook]] with 22, [[Sachin Tendulkar|Tendulkar]] with 19, [[Steve Smith (cricketer)|Steve Smith]] got his 15th after his 27th birthday) due to NZ's lean Test schedule. \n\nHe was also named as 12th man in the 'Team of the Tournament' at the 2017 Champions Trophy by the ICC and Cricinfo.<ref>https://www.icc-cricket.com/champions-trophy/media-releases/421165</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/19678837/captain-sarfraz-pips-kohli-tamim-no-3|title=Champions Trophy XI: Sarfraz pips Kohli, Tamim at No. 3|website=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2018, Williamson scored the most [[List of New Zealand Test cricket records#Most career centuries|\ncenturies by a New Zealand batsman in Tests]] (18).<ref name=\"KW18\">{{citeweb|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/cricket/102538870/kane-williamson-notches-18th-test-century-the-most-by-a-new-zealander|title=Kane Williamson notches 18th test century, the most by a New Zealander|work=Stuff NZ |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, he was one of twenty players to be awarded a new contract for the 2018\u201319 season by [[New Zealand Cricket]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23512513/todd-astle-bags-first-new-zealand-contract |title=Todd Astle bags his first New Zealand contract |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, Williamson scored his 10,000th run in first-class cricket, batting for the English side [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]] in the [[2018 County Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/844084 |title=Kane Williamson goes past 10,000-run mark in first-class cricket |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref> On 8 December 2018, he scored his 19th test century in the deciding 3rd game in the Pakistan away series. This century was his 6th in the team's second batting innings, but he was dismissed for the first time in 6 innings, giving him an average of 865 runs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BrGHm5PFLLu/|title=ESPN Cricinfo on Instagram: \u201cA first in Tests for Kane Williamson: being dismissed after scoring a hundred in the team's second innings. And don't miss that average\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> On 7 December 2018, Williamson became the first player from New Zealand to cross 900 rating points in the ICC Test batting rankings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/105579/kane-williamson-breaches-900-points-barrier-new-zealand-icc-rankings|title=Kane Williamson breaches 900-points barrier|website=Cricbuzz|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> For his performances in 2018, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC.<ref>https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/980936</ref> He was also named as captain of the Test XI by ESPNCricinfo and named in the Test XI by Cricbuzz.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2018/content/story/1169902.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/105896/2018-test-team-of-the-year|title=2018 Test team of the year\n|work=Cricbuzz |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2019, during the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in New Zealand in 2018\u201319#Test series|test series against Bangladesh]], Williamson scored 200 not out where New Zealand posted their highest ever total of 715 in a test innings, he also became the fastest New Zealand player to score 6,000 runs in test cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26115274/new-zealand-biggest-total-mehidy-horror-match|title=New Zealand's biggest total, and Mehidy's horror match|date=2019-03-02|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1083252|title=Bangladesh slide after Williamson\u2019s double in record total|website=www.icc-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he was named the captain of [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#New Zealand|New Zealand's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26426227/sodhi-blundell-named-new-zealand-world-cup-squad |title=Sodhi and Blundell named in New Zealand World Cup squad |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1154328 |title=Uncapped Blundell named in New Zealand World Cup squad, Sodhi preferred to Astle |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\nAt the 2019 Cricket World Cup, he scored an unbeaten 106 to guide New Zealand to victory over South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/48696448|title= Cricket World Cup: Kane Williamson's majestic 106 sees New Zealand beat South Africa|work=BBC |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> In the same match, Williamson scored his 3,000th run as captain of New Zealand in ODIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/masterful-williamson-nudges-south-africa-closer-world-cup-exit-1 |title=Masterful Williamson nudges South Africa closer to World Cup exit |work=Loop News Barbados |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> On 22 June, Williamson scored 148 runs off 154 balls in a 5 run victory over [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], this was also his career best score in ODI cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/icc-world-cup/icc-world-cup-kane-williamson-oozes-class-with-second-straight-century/articleshow/69910989.cms|title=ICC World Cup: Kane Williamson oozes class with second straight century - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> One week later, in the match against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], Williamson became the third-fastest bastman, in terms of innings, to score 6,000 runs in ODIs, doing so in his 139th innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12245165 |title=While You Were Sleeping: Ugly scenes mar World Cup clash |work=NZ Herald |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref> At the end of the World Cup, he was awarded the Player of the Tournament award after becoming the highest scoring captain in a single World Cup, making 578 runs in 10 matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/15/kane-williamsons-class-reaction-told-won-cricket-world-cup-player-series-10315328/|title=Kane Williamson's class reaction to winning World Cup player of the series award|date=2019-07-15|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref> He was named as captain of the 'Team of the Tournament' by the ICC and ESPNCricinfo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1278701/featured|title=CWC19: Team of the Tournament |work=ICC |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27210608/starc-archer-ferguson-bumrah-espncricinfo-2019-world-cup-xi |title= Starc, Archer, Ferguson, Bumrah in ESPNcricinfo's 2019 World Cup XI|work=ESPNCricinfo |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/we-are-still-thinking-about-it-kane-williamson-on-world-cup-final-loss/articleshow/71077251.cms|title=We are still thinking about it: Kane Williamson on World Cup final loss - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/cricketnext/news/icc-world-cup-2019-kane-williamson-new-zealands-playmaker-and-backbone-at-world-cup-2222487.html|title=ICC World Cup 2019: Kane Williamson \u2013 New Zealand\u2019s Playmaker And Backbone|date=2019-07-09|website=News18|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==International centuries==\n{{main|List of international cricket centuries by Kane Williamson}}\n{{As of|2019|12}}, Williamson has scored 21 Test and 13 ODI centuries.\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliamson has a twin brother named Logan, who is a few minutes younger than him. The twins are the youngest of five children, and the siblings are girls. Kane and Logan have both excelled at several sports, including rugby, field hockey, basketball, volleyball, soccer and cricket.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|title = The Vault: Kane Williamson \u2013 Black Cap in waiting|url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11410866|newspaper = New Zealand Herald|date = 2015-03-03|access-date = 2015-12-22|issn = 1170-0777|language = en-NZ}}</ref> Williamson's childhood hero was [[Sachin Tendulkar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisdenindia.com/player/New-Zealand/Kane-Williamson/3597.html|title=Kane Williamson \u2013 New Zealand \u2013 Cricket Stats and Records \u2013 Wisden India|work=wisdenindia.com|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[New Zealand cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2014\u201315|New Zealand vs Pakistan 2014 ODI series]], Williamson donated his entire match fee for all five ODIs to the victims of the [[2014 Peshawar school massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/cricket/pakistan-attack-new-zealands-kane-4869403|title=Pakistan attack: New Zealand's Kane Williamson and Adam Milne donate match fees to Peshawar victims|author=James Whaling|date=23 December 2014|work=mirror|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport360.com/article/international/30527/kane-williamson-and-adam-milne-donate-match-fee-peshawar-victims|title=Kane Williamson and Adam Milne donate match-fee to Peshawar victims|work=sport360.com|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> He bowls and bats right handed but writes left handed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/cricket/74223576/undefined|title=How Black Caps captain Kane Williamson finds the right balance|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=277906}}\n*[http://www.howstat.com/cricket/Statistics/Players/PlayerOverview.asp?PlayerID=3817 Kane Williamson at Howstat]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Player of the Match awards (cricket)|World Cup Player of the Series]] winner\n| before = [[Mitchell Starc]]\n| after = \u2013\n| years = 2019\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Brendon McCullum]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Halberg Awards|New Zealand's Sportsman of the Year]] | years=2015}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Mah\u00e9 Drysdale]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Current national cricket captains}}\n{{Player of the Series in ICC Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= New Zealand captains\n|bg= black\n|fg= white\n|bordercolor=silver\n|list1=\n{{New Zealand Test Cricket Captains}}\n{{New Zealand ODI Cricket Captains}}\n{{New Zealand T20I Cricket Captains}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= New Zealand squads \n|bg= black\n|fg= white\n|bordercolor=silver\n|list1=\n{{New Zealand Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{New Zealand Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{New Zealand Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Batsmen with a Test batting average above 50}}\n{{Sunrisers Hyderabad Squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, Kane}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cricketers who made a century on Test debut]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2019 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Gloucestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Northern Districts cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Tauranga]]\n[[Category:Sunrisers Hyderabad cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wisden Leading Cricketers in the World]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Century]]\n[[Category:Yorkshire cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|New Zealand cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Kane Williamson\n| fullname = Kane Stuart Williamson\n| image = Kane Williamson in 2019.jpg\n| caption = Williamson, captaining New Zealand, in 2019\n| nickname = <!-- please cite nicknames if they're not on CricInfo -->\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|8|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Tauranga]], New Zealand\n| heightft = 5\n| heightinch = 8\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[off-break]]\n| role = [[Batting order (cricket)|Batsman]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2010-present\n| country = New Zealand\n| testdebutdate = 4 November\n| testdebutyear = 2010\n| testdebutagainst = India\n| testcap = 248\n| lasttestdate = 29 February\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = India\n| odidebutdate = 10 August\n| odidebutyear = 2010\n| odidebutagainst = India\n| odicap = 161\n| lastodidate = 13 March\n| lastodiyear = 2020\n| lastodiagainst = Australia\n| T20Idebutdate = 16 October\n| T20Idebutyear = 2011\n| T20Idebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| T20Icap = 49\n| lastT20Idate = 29 January\n| lastT20Iyear = 2020\n| lastT20Iagainst = India\n| club1 = [[Northern Districts cricket team|Northern Districts]]\n| year1 = {{nowrap|2007/08\u2013present}}\n| club2 = [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]]\n| year2 = 2011\u20132012\n| club3 = [[Yorkshire Cricket Club|Yorkshire]]\n| year3 = 2013\u20132018\n| club4 = [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]]\n| year4 = 2015\u2013present\n| club6 = [[Barbados Tridents]]\n| year6 = 2017\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 80\n| runs1 = 6,476\n| bat avg1 = 50.99\n| 100s/50s1 = 21/32\n| top score1 = 242[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries1 = 2,103\n| wickets1 = 29\n| bowl avg1 = 40.62\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 4/44\n| catches/stumpings1 = 71/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 151\n| runs2 = 6,173\n| bat avg2 = 47.48\n| 100s/50s2 = 13/39\n| top score2 = 148\n| deliveries2 = 1,467\n| wickets2 = 37\n| bowl avg2 = 35.40\n| fivefor2 = 0\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 4/22\n| catches/stumpings2 = 60/\u2013\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n| matches3 = 60\n| runs3 = 1,665\n| bat avg3 = 32.64\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/11\n| top score3 = 95\n| deliveries3 = 118\n| wickets3 = 6\n| bowl avg3 = 27.33\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 2/16\n| catches/stumpings3 = 27/\u2013\n| column4 = [[First class cricket|FC]]\n| matches4 = 147\n| runs4 = 11,279\n| bat avg4 = 48.82\n| 100s/50s4 = 31/59\n| top score4 = 284[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries4 = 6,576\n| wickets4 = 85\n| bowl avg4 = 43.43\n| fivefor4 = 1\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 5/75\n| catches/stumpings4 = 135/\u2013\n| date = 13 March \n| year = 2020\n| source = http://espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/277906.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Kane Stuart Williamson''' (born 8 August 1990) is a New Zealand international [[cricket]]er who is currently the [[Captain (cricket)|captain]] of the [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand national team]] in all formats. He is a right-handed batsman and an occasional [[off spin]] bowler.  Williamson made his [[first-class cricket]] debut in December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/159/159052/First-Class_Matches.html|title=List of First Class Matches Played by Kane Williamson|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref> He made his U-19 debut against the touring [[India Under-19 cricket team|Indian U-19 team]] the same year and was named captain of the [[New Zealand Under-19 cricket team|New Zealand U-19 team]] for the [[2008 U-19 Cricket World Cup]]. He made his international debut in 2010. Williamson has represented New Zealand at the [[2011 ICC Cricket World Cup|2011]], [[2015 ICC Cricket World Cup|2015]] and [[2019 ICC Cricket World Cup|2019]] editions of the [[Cricket World Cup]] and [[2012 ICC World Twenty20|2012]], [[2014 ICC World Twenty20|2014]] and [[2016 ICC World Twenty20|2016]] editions of the [[ICC World Twenty20]]. He made his full-time captaincy debut for [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] in the 2016 ICC World Twenty20 in [[India]]. He captained [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand national team]] in [[2019 Cricket World Cup]] and led the team to the finals. He was then awarded the [[Cricket World Cup awards#Awards summary |Player of the Tournament]] award. \n\nAt various times [[Ian Chappell]] and [[Martin Crowe]] have ranked Williamson among the top four or five Test cricket batsmen, along with [[Joe Root]], [[Steve Smith (cricketer)|Steve Smith]], [[Virat Kohli]] and [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Test cricket's young Fab Four|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/774705.html|publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Virat Kohli, Joe Root, Steven Smith, Kane Williamson \u2018Fab Four\u2019 of Tests: Martin Crowe|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/virat-kohli-joe-root-steven-smith-kane-williamson-fab-four-of-tests-martin-crowe/|publisher=The Indian Express |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/20727319/big-four-ought-five-warner-there|title=Big four? What about Warner?|work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKane Williamson was born on 8 August 1990 in [[Tauranga]], New Zealand. He played senior representative cricket at the age of 14 and first-class cricket at 16. Williamson attended [[Tauranga Boys' College]] from 2004\u20132008, where he was head boy in his final year and was coached by Pacey Depina. Depina described Williamson as having \"a thirst to be phenomenal \u2013 but not at anyone else's expense.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cumming|first1=Geoff|title=More than able Kane|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11413192|website=NZ Herald|publisher=NZ Herald|accessdate=2015-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Kane Williamson: 19 facts about the Kiwi superstar|url = http://www.criclife.com/lists/chronicles/kane-williamson-19-facts-about-the-kiwi-superstar-43820|website = CricLife|date = 2015-08-08|accessdate = 2015-12-22}}</ref> He reportedly scored 40 centuries before he left school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecricketmonthly.com/story/879501/kane-is-able|title=Kane is able|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Domestic career ==\n=== Northern Districts ===\nWilliamson made his debut for Northern Districts in 2007 at the age of 17, who he has remained with for the duration of his New Zealand domestic career.\n\n=== English county cricket ===\nWilliamson signed for [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]] to play in the [[2011 English cricket season|2011 English county season]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Williamson joins Gloucestershire|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/505808.html|work=ESPNCricinfo|date=12 March 2011|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> On 14 August 2013, he signed for [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]] for the rest of the season and subsequently signed to return for the [[2014 English cricket season|2014 season]], when his side won the County Championship.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Yorkshire sign New Zealand batsman Kane Williamson |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/23695847 |work=BBC Sport|date=14 August 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Yorkshire: Kane Williamson to be overseas player for 2014 season |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/24224196 |work=BBC Sport|date=24 September 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> He signed to return the latter part of the [[2015 English cricket season|2015 season]], but when incumbent overseas player [[Aaron Finch]] was not selected for the Australia ODI squad, Yorkshire ultimately chose to extend Finch's deal in place of Williamson.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Kane Williamson: Yorkshire re-sign New Zealand batsman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/31518727 |work=BBC Sport|date=18 February 2015 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Williamson not required after Finch returns |url=http://www.ecb.co.uk/news/articles/williamson-not-required-after-finch-returns |work=ECB |date=21 August 2015 |accessdate=27 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203124627/http://www.ecb.co.uk/news/articles/williamson-not-required-after-finch-returns |archive-date=3 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He subsequently signed a deal for part of the [[2016 English cricket season|2016 season]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Kane Williamson: Yorkshire re-sign New Zealand batsman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/35417777 |work=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2016 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Indian Premier League (IPL) ===\nOn 6 February 2015, [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]] of the IPL signed Williamson for US$96,500. He played for Sunrisers Hyderabad in the [[2016 Indian Premier League|2016 season]] where they won the title. For the [[2017 Indian Premier League]] he was retained by the side. In the [[List of 2018 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2018 IPL Auction]], he was retained by the Sunrisers Hyderabad for US$460,500. On 29 March 2018, he was announced captain of Sunrisers Hyderabad replacing [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/SunRisers/status/979263226746753024|title=SunRisers Hyderabad on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/101315/kane-williamson-appointed-sunrisers-hyderabad-cricket-team-captain-for-ipl-2018|title=Kane Williamson appointed SRH captain for IPL 2018 He also won the Orange cap (leading run scorer) on the same edition.In the 2019 version of Vivo IPL he transferred his captaincy duties to Bhuvneshwar Kumar because of his shoulder injury not allowing him to play some games.|work=Cricbuzz|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en}}</ref> Under Williamson's captaincy Sunrisers Hyderabad finished runners-up after [[Chennai Super Kings]] defeated them in the [[2018 Indian Premier League Final|final]] by 8 wickets, he also won the [[Orange Cap]] for scoring the most runs (735) in the [[2018 Indian Premier League|2018 IPL season]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/cricketnext/news/ipl-2018-kane-williamson-takes-orange-cap-becomes-third-highest-scorer-in-single-season-1761105.html|title=IPL 2018: Kane Williamson Takes Orange Cap, Becomes Third Highest-scorer in Single Season|date=2018-05-28|work=News18|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> He was named in the IPL XI of the tournament by Cricbuzz.<ref>https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/102276/cb-xi-team-of-ipl-2018</ref>\n\n===Other franchise cricket===\nIn June 2019, he was selected to play for the Edmonton Royals franchise team in the [[2019 Global T20 Canada]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadacricket.com/?p=12755 |title=Global T20 draft streamed live |work=Canada Cricket Online |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n=== Early days ===\nWilliamson was 17, when he led the New Zealand Under-19 side in the World Cup in Malaysia in 2008. New Zealand reached the semi-final, where they lost to the eventual champions India. On 24 March 2010, Williamson was named in the New Zealand Test squad for the second Test against Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/nzvaus2010/content/current/story/453236.html|title=Kane Williamson named in New Zealand Test squad|last=Coverdale|first=Brydon|date=24 March 2010|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=24 March 2010}}</ref> but ultimately he did not play in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/nzvaus2010/engine/current/match/423790.html|title=Scorecard \u2013 2nd Test: New Zealand v Australia at Hamilton, 27\u201331&nbsp;March 2010|publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate=6 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson made his [[One-Day International]] debut against [[India national cricket team|India]] on 10 August 2010. He was dismissed for a 9th ball [[Duck (cricket)|duck]]. In his second match, he was bowled by [[Angelo Mathews]] for a second ball duck. He scored his maiden ODI [[Century (cricket)|century]] against [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]] on 14 October 2010 in [[Dhaka]] and hence became the youngest centurion in New Zealand's cricket history. Due to his performance on the [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2010\u201311|Bangladesh tour]] where New Zealand suffered a 4\u20130 whitewash, Williamson was selected in the New Zealand Test squad for the [[New Zealand cricket team in India in 2010\u201311|tour of India]] that followed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india-v-new-zealand-2010/content/current/story/483282.html|title=Williamson, Bennett in Test squad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson made his [[Test cricket]] debut against [[India national cricket team|India]] at [[Ahmedabad]] on 4 November 2010. In his first innings he scored 131 runs off 299 balls and became the eighth [[List of Test cricket records for New Zealand#Centuries|New Zealand player to score a century on Test debut]].<ref name=\"TestDebut\">{{cite web|title=ESPNcricinfo : New Zealand tour of India (Nov 2010), 1st Test: India v New Zealand at Ahmedabad, Nov&nbsp;4\u20138, 2010|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india-v-new-zealand-2010/engine/current/match/464531.html|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=6 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/485892.html|title=Williamson and Vettori guide New Zealand past 400|author=Ravindran, Siddarth|date=7 November 2010|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Rising through the ranks ===\nHe was selected in the 2nd XI of the 2014 ICC World T20 Cup by ESPNCricinfo.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/world-t20/content/story/735589.html</ref> He was also named in the Test XI of the year by Cricbuzz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/67765/2014-review-test-team-of-the-year|title=2014 review: Test team of the year\n|work=Cricbuzz |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson scored test match score of 161 against West Indies in June 2014. It was his second test century of the series and helped secure a rare away test series victory for his side. Williamson finished as the leading overall run scorer in the series with 413 runs, and was denied a double century only by rain, which forced skipper [[Brendon McCullum]] to declare in the interest of obtaining a result in the match. He was also reported for a suspect bowling action in April 2014, but was cleared in December 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AihgstaAlp0|title=See Kane Williamson's new bowling action|date=9 December 2014|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sachithra Senanayake & Kane Williamson cleared to bowl again |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/30394969 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 December 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014 }}</ref> His [[illegal bowling action]] started after he left high school in order to get a faster release and turn on the ball.  His new action essentially reverts him to his action in high school, with a more side-on approach and less wrist and elbow deviation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ho3TQNrdsb8|title=Kane Williamson First Test Over With New Bowling Action|date=28 December 2014|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> He was also named as captain ahead of the ODI and Twenty20 series against Pakistan as Brendon McCullum was rested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/67160/kane-williamson-named-as-captain-for-pakistan-series-brendon-mccullum-rested|title=Kane Williamson named as captain for Pakistan series; Brendon McCullum rested|work=Cricbuzz|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kane Williamson (9773667991).jpg|thumb|234x234px|Williamson batting against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] in 2013]]\nWilliamson is currently third on the list (behind Corey Anderson and Jesse Ryder) for the highest ever strike-rated century by a New Zealander in a [[One-Day International]]. He achieved the feat during his 100[[not out|*]] off 69 balls [[New Zealand cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2011\u201312#3rd ODI|against Zimbabwe]] at [[Bulawayo]].<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;orderby=batting_strike_rate;runsmin1=100;runsval1=runs;size=150;team=5;template=results;t Statistics / Statsguru / One-Day Internationals / Batting records] ESPNcricinfo Statsguru. Retrieved 29 December 2011</ref> On 19 September 2014 he scored his first T20 hundred scoring 101[[not out|*]] in 49 balls to guide [[Northern Districts]] for a comfortable win against [[Cape Cobras]] in [[Champions League Twenty20]] 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/champions-league-twenty20-2014/content/story/782333.html|title=Kane Williamson ton crushes Cobras \u2013  Cricket  \u2013 ESPNcricinfo|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>  He has also established one of the most potent no. 3-no. 4 [[Batting order (cricket)#Top order|top-order]] partnership with [[Ross Taylor]], with himself being the most prolific no. 3 batsman for the national side since former captain [[Stephen Fleming]].Apart from Fleming (in 2006), Williamson (in 2015) became the most recent no. 3 New Zealand batsmen to score a double century in Test cricket. However, Williamson and Taylor were also involved in 12 run outs across all forms of international cricket as of 26 January 2015 when they are both on the crease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/sport/black-caps-await-final-one-dayer-before-world-cup-2015012620|title=Black Caps await final one dayer before World Cup \u2013 Sport \u2013 3 News|author=David Di Somma|work=3news.co.nz|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> As a fielder, his position is predominantly at gully,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FeD7CQrtV8U|title=Kane Williamson Incredible Gully Catch vs. Sri Lanka (Wellington 2015)|date=6 January 2015|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> but can move to point with spin bowlers, or cover point or long off with fast bowlers.\n\nIn 2015, he started with 69 and 242[[not out|*]] against Sri Lanka, with two catches in the field in a man-of-the-match performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-sri-lanka-2014-15/content/story/817747.html|title=Williamson could be our greatest ever batter \u2013 McCullum|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>  On 3 February 2015, he helped New Zealand score the 99th ODI century in the team's history against Pakistan; Ross Taylor scored the 100th in the same match. He also scored over 700 runs before the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]] in just the first two months of the calendar year. On 17 June 2015 he became the fifth-fastest batsmen and fastest New Zealander to score 3,000 runs, getting them in just 78 innings. On 15 November 2015 Williamson and Taylor became the first pair of away batsmen to each score 2nd innings centuries at [[List of international cricket centuries at the WACA Ground|WACA Ground]] in [[Perth]].\n\nIn December 2015, during the [[Sri Lankan cricket team in New Zealand in 2015\u201316|second Test against Sri Lanka]], Williamson broke the record for the most Test runs scored in a calendar year by a New Zealander, with 1172 runs.<ref name=\"2ndTest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-sri-lanka-2015-16/content/story/953745.html |title=Williamson's record ton and NZ's longest unbeaten streak at home |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 December 2015| accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> He also ended 2015 with 2692 runs, the highest score across all forms of international cricket for the year, and third highest totals in a single year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=555268464622721&set=o.203262656377121&type=3&theater|title=William Q\u00fcensell|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor his performances in 2015, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC, Cricbuzz and ESPNCricinfo.<ref>https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/182259</ref><ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2015/content/story/956299.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/76936/cricbuzz-team-of-the-year-2015|title=Cricbuzz Team of the Year 2015\n|work=Cricbuzz |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> He was also named in the ODI XI of the year 2015 by Cricinfo.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2015/content/story/956299.html</ref>\n\nHe was awarded the T20 Player of the Year by NZC for the 2014-15 season.<ref>http://nzcricketmuseum.co.nz/new-zealand-cricket-awards/</ref>\n\n=== Captaincy ===\nIn March 2016, Williamson assumed the position of captain of New Zealand across all forms of cricket after the retirement of Brendon McCullum, beginning with the World T20I cup in India. He was named as captain of the 'Team of the Tournament' by Cricinfo and Cricbuzz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/995203.html|title=ESPNcricinfo's team of the 2016 World T20|website=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/79133/cricbuzz-team-of-the-icc-world-t20-2016|title=Cricbuzz Team of the ICC World T20, 2016|website=Cricbuzz}}</ref> He also picked up NZ player of the year, Test player of the year and the Redpath Cup for top batsman in first class cricket for the second year in a row.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cricket.com.au/news/brendon-mccullum-wins-new-zealand-sir-richard-hadlee-medal-after-world-cup/2015-04-02\n| title = McCullum named cricketer of year\n| website = cricket.com.au\n| access-date = 25 February 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.newshub.co.nz/sport/williamson-cleans-up-at-nz-cricket-awards-2016022521#axzz40q3ulDBA\n| title = Williamson cleans up at NZ Cricket Awards\n| website = Newshub.co.nz\n| access-date = 25 February 2016\n}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, during the [[New Zealand cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2016|Test series against Zimbabwe]], Williamson became the thirteenth batsman to score a century against all the other Test playing nations. He completed this in the fewest innings, the quickest time from his Test debut and became the youngest player to achieve this feat.<ref name=\"WilliamsonZim\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-new-zealand-2016/content/story/1043641.html |title=Williamson racks up the records |accessdate=7 August 2016 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> In the complete list of such batsmen, he has achieved this feat with the smallest number of total centuries.\n\nFor his performances in 2016, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC.<ref>https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/the-full-list-of-icc-awards-2016-winners/story-HwiwPQa1CPLmYV6y7hx6vM.html></ref>\n\nFor his performances in the 2015-16 and 2016-17 seasons, he won the Sir Richard Hadlee Medal.<ref>http://nzcricketmuseum.co.nz/new-zealand-cricket-awards/</ref> He also was awarded the T20 Player of the Year by NZC for the 2016-17 season.<ref>http://nzcricketmuseum.co.nz/new-zealand-cricket-awards/</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2017, Williamson joined [[Ross Taylor]] as joint second highest (first amongst active players) on NZ's Test century list, both one behind [[Martin Crowe]]. Williamson also took the fewest matches to score at least 16 centuries at 26 years of age ([[Alastair Cook|Cook]] with 22, [[Sachin Tendulkar|Tendulkar]] with 19, [[Steve Smith (cricketer)|Steve Smith]] got his 15th after his 27th birthday) due to NZ's lean Test schedule. \n\nHe was also named as 12th man in the 'Team of the Tournament' at the 2017 Champions Trophy by the ICC and Cricinfo.<ref>https://www.icc-cricket.com/champions-trophy/media-releases/421165</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/19678837/captain-sarfraz-pips-kohli-tamim-no-3|title=Champions Trophy XI: Sarfraz pips Kohli, Tamim at No. 3|website=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2018, Williamson scored the most [[List of New Zealand Test cricket records#Most career centuries|\ncenturies by a New Zealand batsman in Tests]] (18).<ref name=\"KW18\">{{citeweb|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/cricket/102538870/kane-williamson-notches-18th-test-century-the-most-by-a-new-zealander|title=Kane Williamson notches 18th test century, the most by a New Zealander|work=Stuff NZ |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, he was one of twenty players to be awarded a new contract for the 2018\u201319 season by [[New Zealand Cricket]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23512513/todd-astle-bags-first-new-zealand-contract |title=Todd Astle bags his first New Zealand contract |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, Williamson scored his 10,000th run in first-class cricket, batting for the English side [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]] in the [[2018 County Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/844084 |title=Kane Williamson goes past 10,000-run mark in first-class cricket |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref> On 8 December 2018, he scored his 19th test century in the deciding 3rd game in the Pakistan away series. This century was his 6th in the team's second batting innings, but he was dismissed for the first time in 6 innings, giving him an average of 865 runs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BrGHm5PFLLu/|title=ESPN Cricinfo on Instagram: \u201cA first in Tests for Kane Williamson: being dismissed after scoring a hundred in the team's second innings. And don't miss that average\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> On 7 December 2018, Williamson became the first player from New Zealand to cross 900 rating points in the ICC Test batting rankings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/105579/kane-williamson-breaches-900-points-barrier-new-zealand-icc-rankings|title=Kane Williamson breaches 900-points barrier|website=Cricbuzz|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> For his performances in 2018, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC.<ref>https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/980936</ref> He was also named as captain of the Test XI by ESPNCricinfo and named in the Test XI by Cricbuzz.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2018/content/story/1169902.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/105896/2018-test-team-of-the-year|title=2018 Test team of the year\n|work=Cricbuzz |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2019, during the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in New Zealand in 2018\u201319#Test series|test series against Bangladesh]], Williamson scored 200 not out where New Zealand posted their highest ever total of 715 in a test innings, he also became the fastest New Zealand player to score 6,000 runs in test cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26115274/new-zealand-biggest-total-mehidy-horror-match|title=New Zealand's biggest total, and Mehidy's horror match|date=2019-03-02|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1083252|title=Bangladesh slide after Williamson\u2019s double in record total|website=www.icc-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he was named the captain of [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#New Zealand|New Zealand's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26426227/sodhi-blundell-named-new-zealand-world-cup-squad |title=Sodhi and Blundell named in New Zealand World Cup squad |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1154328 |title=Uncapped Blundell named in New Zealand World Cup squad, Sodhi preferred to Astle |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\nAt the 2019 Cricket World Cup, he scored an unbeaten 106 to guide New Zealand to victory over South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/48696448|title= Cricket World Cup: Kane Williamson's majestic 106 sees New Zealand beat South Africa|work=BBC |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> In the same match, Williamson scored his 3,000th run as captain of New Zealand in ODIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/masterful-williamson-nudges-south-africa-closer-world-cup-exit-1 |title=Masterful Williamson nudges South Africa closer to World Cup exit |work=Loop News Barbados |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> On 22 June, Williamson scored 148 runs off 154 balls in a 5 run victory over [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], this was also his career best score in ODI cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/icc-world-cup/icc-world-cup-kane-williamson-oozes-class-with-second-straight-century/articleshow/69910989.cms|title=ICC World Cup: Kane Williamson oozes class with second straight century - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> One week later, in the match against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], Williamson became the third-fastest bastman, in terms of innings, to score 6,000 runs in ODIs, doing so in his 139th innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12245165 |title=While You Were Sleeping: Ugly scenes mar World Cup clash |work=NZ Herald |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref> At the end of the World Cup, he was awarded the Player of the Tournament award after becoming the highest scoring captain in a single World Cup, making 578 runs in 10 matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/15/kane-williamsons-class-reaction-told-won-cricket-world-cup-player-series-10315328/|title=Kane Williamson's class reaction to winning World Cup player of the series award|date=2019-07-15|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref> He was named as captain of the 'Team of the Tournament' by the ICC and ESPNCricinfo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1278701/featured|title=CWC19: Team of the Tournament |work=ICC |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27210608/starc-archer-ferguson-bumrah-espncricinfo-2019-world-cup-xi |title= Starc, Archer, Ferguson, Bumrah in ESPNcricinfo's 2019 World Cup XI|work=ESPNCricinfo |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/we-are-still-thinking-about-it-kane-williamson-on-world-cup-final-loss/articleshow/71077251.cms|title=We are still thinking about it: Kane Williamson on World Cup final loss - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/cricketnext/news/icc-world-cup-2019-kane-williamson-new-zealands-playmaker-and-backbone-at-world-cup-2222487.html|title=ICC World Cup 2019: Kane Williamson \u2013 New Zealand\u2019s Playmaker And Backbone|date=2019-07-09|website=News18|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==International centuries==\n{{main|List of international cricket centuries by Kane Williamson}}\n{{As of|2019|12}}, Williamson has scored 21 Test and 13 ODI centuries.\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliamson has a twin brother named Logan, who is a few minutes younger than him. The twins are the youngest of five children, and the siblings are girls. Kane and Logan have both excelled at several sports, including rugby, field hockey, basketball, volleyball, soccer and cricket.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|title = The Vault: Kane Williamson \u2013 Black Cap in waiting|url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11410866|newspaper = New Zealand Herald|date = 2015-03-03|access-date = 2015-12-22|issn = 1170-0777|language = en-NZ}}</ref> Williamson's childhood hero was [[Sachin Tendulkar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisdenindia.com/player/New-Zealand/Kane-Williamson/3597.html|title=Kane Williamson \u2013 New Zealand \u2013 Cricket Stats and Records \u2013 Wisden India|work=wisdenindia.com|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[New Zealand cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2014\u201315|New Zealand vs Pakistan 2014 ODI series]], Williamson donated his entire match fee for all five ODIs to the victims of the [[2014 Peshawar school massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/cricket/pakistan-attack-new-zealands-kane-4869403|title=Pakistan attack: New Zealand's Kane Williamson and Adam Milne donate match fees to Peshawar victims|author=James Whaling|date=23 December 2014|work=mirror|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport360.com/article/international/30527/kane-williamson-and-adam-milne-donate-match-fee-peshawar-victims|title=Kane Williamson and Adam Milne donate match-fee to Peshawar victims|work=sport360.com|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> He bowls and bats right handed but writes left handed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/cricket/74223576/undefined|title=How Black Caps captain Kane Williamson finds the right balance|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=277906}}\n*[http://www.howstat.com/cricket/Statistics/Players/PlayerOverview.asp?PlayerID=3817 Kane Williamson at Howstat]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Player of the Match awards (cricket)|World Cup Player of the Series]] winner\n| 